<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Government's Economic Approach Attacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The economic policy of the
British government was challenged again Wednesday as Barratt
Developments, the UK's second biggest private housebuilder, said
that the government was responsible for three major problems
currently facing the housing industry.
</P>
<P>
"Firstly, the government's management of the economy, which is
seriously undermining consumer confidence, and secondly, the
government's negative position on home ownership, especially their
lack of support for first-time buyers," the company's chairman,
Frank Eaton, was quoted by a BBC report as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Thirdly, the government has failed to implement a land
availability policy to meet UK housing needs."
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, another housebuilder, Redrow, attacked
planning delays, saying there appeared to be "little political
will" at central and government level to address a UK housing
shortage.
</P>
<P>
However, Barratt's announced a 33 percent jump in pre-tax
profits in the six months to June to make a record 93.3 million
pounds (152 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The company said market conditions it faced remained favorable
across the UK and in the U.S. where its Southern California
operations also improved their position.
</P>
<P>
"Since the spring, there has been some slowing in the UK
marketplace and overall activity in the Southeast has adjusted to
a more normal and sustainable level," Eaton said.
</P>
<P>
But other UK regions are continuing at a similar level to the
year just ended and the company has no doubt that the underlying
demand for new houses will remain strong, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
