<HEADLINE> Fans ID Cards to Be Introduced in Hungary Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A compulsory identity card
will be used to control soccer hooliganism in next season,
according to Attila Kovacs, head of the Hungarian Football
Federation (MLSZ) here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The card system would be accompanied by other moves aimed at
increasing security in stadiums and driving hooligans out of the
game, Kovacs said.
</P>
<P>
Kovacs said the precise workings of the identity card scheme
had not yet been decided but only fans with the card would be
able to buy tickets or enter stadiums.
</P>
<P>
Hooliganism has been on the rise in Hungary and some of the
worst violence came at the Budapest derby on Saturday between
Ujpest and Ferencvaros.
</P>
<P>
Ferencvaros fans went on the rampage following their team's
2-1 defeat, trashing seating and throwing stones before riot
police intervened with teargas.
</P>
<P>
Fans fought a running battle with police in the streets
surrounding the stadium, smashing cars and shop windows and
hurling road signs at the police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
