<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, September 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine government Wednesday mourned the loss
of Philippine Airlines (PAL) hours before its scheduled shutdown
at midnight after 57 years of service.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada told reporters that he had already
done all he could to save the airline from closing down.
</P>
<P>
"I have already exhausted all remedies to settle this dispute
between labor and management so if they do not agree by midnight,
everything is over. PAL is lost," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier press briefing, Estrada's spokesman Jerry Barican
said the government was saddened with the loss of Asia's first
airline. (Philippines-Airline-Shutdown)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Secretary of State for Northern Ireland Mo
Mowlam said Wednesday the Irish Republican Army's arsenal would be
scrapped and progress was being made in implementing the
province's peace deal on disarmament.
</P>
<P>
"I consider that progress is being made because it's no longer
a question of if decommissioning is going to take place -- it's a
question of when," Mowlam told reporters in Dublin after meeting
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern.
</P>
<P>
The secretary also made clear that she believed the issue would
be solved in the end, just as a peace deal was eventually signed
in April after nearly two years of stop-start talks.
</P>
<P>
"As so often has happened in this process over the months, you
begin to look for momentum and make progress step by step. That is
what's happening," she said. (UK-N.Ireland-Arms)
</P>
