<HEADLINE> Tanzania Repatriates 16 Foreigners After Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen foreigners have
been repatriated following the bombing of U.S. embassy in Tanzania,
local police said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A police officer, who asked not to be named, told Xinhua that some
of the repatriated foreigners are Arabians.
</P>
<P>
"We have pressured them, but... you cannot hold them if you have no
evidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
The bomb blast which took place on August 7 in Dar es Salaam,
the country's capital, killed 11 people including 10 Tanzanians
and one Kenyan and injured more than 70 others.
</P>
<P>
So far, two suspects, including one Tanzanian from Zanzibar, have
been arraigned by a resident magistrate court in Dar es Salaam, facing
charges of murdering 11 people. They will be tried by High Court on
October 5.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the police released on condition three suspects,
including a local businessman, a Tanzanian and an Algerian. The
three people could be detained again if found guilty.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, about 30 people were held by the police during the
preliminary investigations of the case, but most of them have been
released after interrogation.
</P>
<P>
The police indicated that other suspects directly involved in the
bombing are still at large outside the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
