<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Rejects Turkish Cypriots' Proposal for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government has
outrightly rejected a proposal from the Turkish Cypriot side for
examining the disputes over property rights in Cyprus which
resulted from the Turkish military intervention in 1974.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement released here Wednesday, Cypriot
government spokesman Christos Stylianides said "there is no
Security Council resolution or decision by the Human Rights Court
which refers to exchange of property, as the Turkish side
proposes."
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash proposed Tuesday that an
independent, autonomous commission be set up to identify formulae
and criteria concerning property between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"For a solution to the Cyprus problem there are a number of
elements. One of these is the exchange of property, without this
there can be no agreement," Denktash said.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said the Cypriot government believes Denktash's
proposal is part of his efforts to achieve recognition of his
illegal breakaway regime unilaterally declared in northern Cyprus
in 1983.
</P>
<P>
He cited Security Council resolutions and European Court of
Human Rights decision which all call for the refugees' return to
the Turkish-occupied northern Cyprus and enjoyment of their
property.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Some 200,000 Greek Cypriots became refugees after they fled or
were expelled from their towns and villages in the north
following the Turkish invasion. Part of their property was taken
by some 40,000 Turkish Cypriots who fled from south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
