<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Closes Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Airlines (PAL) was
totally shut down at midnight Wednesday after the breakdown of the
last-ditch reconciliation talks between the management and labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
During the marathon talks mediated by the Labor Department,
both the management and the Philippine Airlines Employees
Association (PALEA), the largest trade union in PAL, refused to
give in to each other.
</P>
<P>
PALEA spokesman Avelino Cavili told reporters after the talks
that union leaders still can not accept the management's
co-ownership proposal and the talks reached a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Senior vice president of PAL Rolando Estavillo said that PALEA
wanted the Labor Department to hold another referendum among its
members on the ownership-sharing proposal.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, the Department of Labor and Employment can not
call any referendum. In that case, we are closed at 12 midnight,"
Estavillo said.
</P>
<P>
Estavillo said the management was unwilling to negotiate
anymore and has already begun paperwork for liquidation of PAL
assets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
