<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debt-ridden Philippine Airlines Closes Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The debt-ridden and
strike-crippled Philippine Airlines (PAL) was totally shut down at
midnight Wednesday after 57 years of service, leaving nearly 9,000
employees jobless.
</P>
<P>
The airline, Asia's oldest and the country's largest, closed
shop after the management and labor unions failed to forge an
acceptable arrangement to ensure industrial peace at the troubled
flag carrier.
</P>
<P>
The last-minute reconciliation talks between the management and
the labor unions broke down as the unions still refused to accept
the management's co-ownership offer to guarantee the company's
industrial peace.
</P>
<P>
During the marathon talks mediated by the labor department,
both the management and the Philippine Airlines Employees
Association (PALEA), the largest trade union in PAL, refused to
give in to each other.
</P>
<P>
PALEA spokesman Avelino Cavili told reporters after the talks
that union leaders still could not accept the management's
co-ownership proposal and the talks reached a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Senior vice president of PAL Rolando Estavillo said that PALEA
wanted the labor department to hold another referendum among its
members on the ownership-sharing proposal.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, the Department of Labor and Employment can not
call any referendum. In that case, we are closed at 12 midnight,"
Estavillo said.
</P>
<P>
Estavillo said the management was unwilling to negotiate
anymore and has already begun paperwork for liquidation of PAL
assets.
</P>
<P>
PAL's management last week decided to close down the company
Wednesday night after PALEA rescinded an earlier agreement and
refused to accept the co-ownership scheme.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, the unions would get 20 percent of PAL shares
and three seats in the PAL board in exchange for a 10-year
suspension on their collective bargaining agreements (CBA). Every
employee would receive 60,000 shares worth 300,000 pesos (6,900
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The suspension of CBA was a key requirement for PAL's
rehabilitation plan which has yet to be approved by the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
PAL said earlier that with no fresh capital infusion, it cannot
operate viably in the face of enormous losses amid the harsh
business environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Start for UK's Controversial Drug Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The UK's troubled drug
development company British Biotech has announced mounting
first-quarter pre-tax losses of 9.2 million pounds (about 15
million U.S. dollars) as it embarks on new leadership, a new
financial plan and more clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
As McCullagh will be replaced by Elliot Goldstein, a senior
executive at SmithKline Beecham, Christopher Hampson, who worked
for chemicals giant ICI from 1956 to 1994, will take over from
John Raisman as chairman.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Biotech announced late-stage trials of its
pancreatitis drug Zacutex in a related condition.
</P>
<P>
The company said it had begun a 1,800 patient Phase III study
of the drug's effectiveness on preventing the development of acute
pancreatitis.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to disentangle itself from the controversies of
the past year, McCullagh, who founded the company in 1986, agreed
to stand down this month to end the "uncertainty" created by the
"unfounded" allegations.
</P>
<P>
The company went into trouble with the controversial sacking in
April of its research director Dr. Andy Millar, after his
allegations that Biotech had exaggerated the success of trials for
the anti-cancer drug Marimastat. His claims sparked a collapse of
confidence among investors and a collapse in the firm's share
price.
</P>
<P>
The company said it would seek to build long term value for
shareholders from the company's position as world leader in the
development of matrix metalloproteinase inhibitors, through the
development of Marimastat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
