<HEADLINE> Iranian News Agency's Director, Editor Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Two detained staff members of
the Iranian official news agency IRNA were released Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The agency said in a report that its deputy managing director
Mohammad Reza Sadeq and chief editor of social news desk Ali Reza
Khosrawi were released after head of the Foundation for the
Oppressed and Disabled Mohsen Rafiqdoust withdrew his complaint.
</P>
<P>
The two IRNA journalists were detained on Tuesday following
five hours of questioning after Rafiqdoust lodged a complaint
against them in connection with a report on an assassination
attempt on him.
</P>
<P>
IRNA's editors and journalists on Wednesday protested the
detention and called for their "immediate and unconditional
release."
</P>
<P>
On September 13, an unknown gunman opened fire on Rafiqdoust
from a hill overlooking his office at the headquarters of the
foundation, but Rafiqdoust escaped the assassination without any
injury.
</P>
<P>
IRNA's special service reported that the assailant was a
disgruntled war disabled who was not satisfied with the
performance of Rafiqdoust as head of a foundation which is
responsible for taking care of the war disabled.
</P>
<P>
Rafiqdoust lodged a complaint against IRNA about the identity
of his assailant.
</P>
<P>
It was the second time within 10 days that some jounalists were
arrested in Iran following the warning of supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei against the tendency of "freedom abuse" in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the moderate daily Tous, which was named after an
ancient Iranian city, was banned and some editors of the daily
were detained by the conservative Judiciary.
</P>
<P>
However, the detentions aroused critical reaction from the
Iranian mass media, which believed that the judiciary
misinterpreted Khamenei's remarks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
