<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM on Nuclear Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China had all along
stood for the complete prohibition and thorough destruction of
nuclear weapons, China stressed here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd Session of the General Assembly of the
United Nations, Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan said that in
the post cold-war period of today, prevention of nuclear
proliferation and endeavor for nuclear disarmament represented a
fervent appeal of the people of all countries.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that back in 1994, the Chinese government proposed to
the U.N. General Assembly that a comprehensive test ban treaty
should be concluded through negotiations, and furthermore, the
Chinese government had on many occasions called on all the other
nuclear states to undertake not to use or threaten to use nuclear
weapons against non-nuclear states and nuclear-free-zones.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said China also proposed to conclude a
convention on no-first-use of nuclear weapons through
negotiations and called for an early negotiation of the Fissile
Material Cut-off Treaty (FMCT).
</P>
<P>
Tang said China was active in the negotiations of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) and among the first to sign
the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Tang reiterated that China would continue to pursue the
policies of unconditional no-first-use of nuclear weapons and
unconditional no use or threat of use of nuclear weapons against
non-nuclear states and nuclear-free zones and continue to support
the Conference on Disarmament in Geneva to negotiate and conclude
a non-discriminative and verifiable FMCT on the basis of the
agreed mandate.
</P>
<P>
Tang urged countries with the largest nuclear arsenals to
accelerate their nuclear disarmament process.
</P>
<P>
Tang expressed the hope that India and Pakistan would fully
implement the P-5 communique as well as Resolution 1172 of the
Security Council, give up their plans to develop nuclear weapons
and immediately and unconditionally accede to CTBT and the Treaty
on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
