<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Producing countries to Continue Efforts on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Oil ministers of five
oil producing countries agreed here Wednesday to resume
consultations and cooperation aimed at shoring up oil prices, the
Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at a one-day meeting attended by the
oil ministers of Algeria, Iran, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates
and Oman. Among them, Oman is not a member of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
A statement released after the meeting said the ministers
would continue cooperation among themselves and with other oil
producing countries "to study all options and take the measures
required to improve current prices including further oil
production cuts."
</P>
<P>
It said the oil ministers reviewed the present global oil
market conditions and the efforts made by oil producers to
re-stabilize the markets and raise prices to levels that secure
fair and stable revenues for producers.
</P>
<P>
This matter was discussed "due to its importance for
world economy and the interests of both producers and consumers,"
the ministers said in their statement.
</P>
<P>
The ministers "noted the continued improvement in abidance to
output cuts by OPEC member states and other oil producing
countries," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival earlier Wednesday, Iranian Oil Minister Bijan
Zanganeh said that Iran favors further oil output reduction.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh said "everything is possible and negotiable if oil
prices do not rise till next November."
</P>
<P>
Oil prices in the world market plunged sharply in the last few
months to their lowest levels in a decade and fell below the
10-dollar per barrel margin, causing a decline in oil revenues and
forcing oil producing countries to reconsider their further oil
development schemes.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members agreed last June to cut production by 2.6 million
barrels per day and most of them were committed to the oil
reduction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
