<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EDS: Recasts, writes through hke092371--Financial Crisis, Labor Dispute Sink Philippine Airlines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The debt-ridden Philippine
Airlines (PAL) was totally shut down at midnight Wednesday,
leaving nearly 9,000 employees jobless and sending the government
hurrying to cushion the adverse effects of the closure.
</P>
<P>
The 57-year-old airline, Asia's oldest and the country's
largest, closed shop after the management and labor unions failed
to forge an acceptable arrangement to ensure industrial peace at
the troubled flag carrier.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Philippine government has started implementing
emergency measures to minimize the economic disruption to be
caused by the closure of PAL whose service has been vital to the
archipelago country.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said the government has
received commitments from at least four local airlines to
immediately expand their operations so they can ply the domestic
routes PAL will abandon starting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
President Joseph Estrada told a government television that he
had exhausted all remedies to settle the labor dispute and the
government will accept whatever happens to PAL.
</P>
<P>
The last-minute reconciliation talks between the management and
the labor unions broke down as the unions still refused to accept
the management's co-ownership offer to guarantee the company's
industrial peace.
</P>
<P>
During the marathon talks mediated by the labor department,
both the management and the Philippine Airlines Employees
Association (PALEA), the largest trade union in PAL, refused to
give in to each other.
</P>
<P>
PALEA spokesman Avelino Cavili told reporters after the talks
that union leaders still could not accept the management's
co-ownership proposal and the talks reached a deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Senior vice president of PAL Rolando Estavillo said that PALEA
wanted the labor department to hold another referendum among its
members on the ownership-sharing proposal.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, the Department of Labor and Employment cannot
call any referendum. In that case, we are closed at 12 midnight,"
Estavillo said.
</P>
<P>
Estavillo said the management was unwilling to negotiate
anymore and has already begun paperwork for liquidation of PAL
assets.
</P>
<P>
PAL's management last week decided to close down the company
Wednesday night after PALEA rescinded an earlier agreement and
refused to accept the co-ownership scheme.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, the unions would get 20 percent of PAL shares
and three seats in the PAL board in exchange for a 10-year
suspension on their collective bargaining agreements (CBA). Every
employee would receive 60,000 shares worth 300,000 pesos (6,900
U.S. dollars)
</P>
<P>
The suspension of CBA was a key requirement for PAL's
rehabilitation plan which has yet to be approved by the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
PAL said earlier that with no fresh capital infusion, PAL could
not operate viably in the face of enormous losses amid the harsh
business environment.
</P>
<P>
PAL, which had incurred huge losses over the past 12 years, has
a debt of 2.1 billion dollars. The company's financial situation
worsened following the regional currency crisis last year and a
devastating 22-day pilots' strike this June.
</P>
<P>
The government has repeatedly ruled out a bailout of the
moribund airline or a takeover of the company.
</P>
<P>
According to Espiritu, Air Philippines and other three smaller
airlines have pledged to upgrade their capacity from 230,000 to
510,000 passengers within the next 25 to 30 days.
</P>
<P>
The government is also ready to speed up the entry of other
airlines that will fill in the void left by PAL, particularly the
domestic routes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
