<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister on Taiwan Question </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The successful return
of Hong Kong and the upcoming return of Macao will undoubtedly
provide useful inspiration and create favorable conditions for the
settlement of the Taiwan question, a senior Chinese official said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan is an inalienable part of China's sacred territory, the
official added.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Tang Jiaxuan, Chinese foreign minister,
was delivering his speech at the 53rd General Assembly session. It
is the first time for Tang, head of the Chinese delegation to the
session, to speak here since he became the Chinese foreign
minister early this year.
</P>
<P>
"We will, as always, adhere to the basic policy of `peaceful
reunification and one country, two systems,' hold on to President
Jiang Zemin's eight-point proposal on developing cross-strait
relations and promoting the process of peaceful reunification of
the motherland, expand cross-strait exchanges and cooperation in
various fields and resolutely oppose the creation of `independence
of Taiwan,' 'two Chinas' and `one China, one Taiwan' and Taiwan's
attempt to re-enter the United Nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan, as a province of China, lacks qualification for the
membership of the United Nations, which groups sovereign states,
and the People's Republic of China is universally recognized as
the solely legitimate representative of the Chinese people as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
"While firmly safeguarding our own sovereignty, we respect the
sovereignty of other countries and vigorously support the efforts
of all countries in the world, and the developing countries in
particular, to defend their state sovereignty," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
