<HEADLINE> Chinese FM on Financial Crisis in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government
had taken a highly responsible attitude following the eruption of
the East Asian financial crisis, China stressed here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd Session of the General Assembly of the
United Nations, Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan said the
East Asian financial crisis had caused a sharp decline of the
economy in many countries of the region and its negative impact
was still spreading.
</P>
<P>
Tang said this crisis occurred in the overall context of
economic globalization, and its impact was being felt across the
world.
</P>
<P>
Tang said to step up international cooperation and put an early
end to the crisis bore on not only the immediate interests of the
East Asian countries, but also the interests of the international
community as a whole, and especially of the developed countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister expressed the hope that those
developed countries with important influence on the region's
economy would shoulder their responsibilities and take active,
resolute and effective measures to make their due contributions to
safeguarding the stability of the financial order and promoting
the recovery and development of the region's economy.
</P>
<P>
Tang said proceeding from the overall interests of maintaining
the stability and development of the region, China had made the
decision not to devalue the RMB yuan, for which China had endured
great pressure and paid a heavy price.
</P>
<P>
Tang said despite growing pressure and risk, China's decision
to maintain the stability of RMB would remain unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
