<HEADLINE> Siemens Agrees to Compensate War-Time Slave Laborers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Germany's electronics and
electrical engineering group Siemens AG announced Wednesday that
it would set up a special fund of 20 million German marks (12
million U.S. dollars) to provide humanitarian relief to
individuals who were forced to work for the company during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
Siemens said in a statement that the fund would be run by
independent managers and organizations with the payments to be
made quickly.
</P>
<P>
According to Siemens' own account, the company employed about
50,000 people "against their will" in 1944 but the total number
could be even higher.
</P>
<P>
Siemens was the second German company to make payments to
war-time slave laborers after the German carmaker Volkswagen,
which also set up a fund of 20 million marks for the same purpose
about two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
A class-action suit against a number of German companies,
including Siemens and Volkswagen, was filed by former slave
laborers last month in the United States to seek compensation.
</P>
</TEXT>
