<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tang on China's Foreign Policy, World Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- China's modernization
drive needs a stable international environment of peace and China
will continue to pursue its independent foreign policy of peace,
Tang Jiaxuan, Chinese foreign minister, said here Wednesday at the
53rd General Assembly session.
</P>
<P>
"This policy is sustained by three pillars: to persist in
independence and keep the initiative, to safeguard world peace,
and to seek common development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To persist in independence and keep the initiative, we always
put our state sovereignty and national security in the first place
and never develop relations with other countries at the expense of
our own sovereignty," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In handling international relations, we stick to non-alignment
and do not go in for military blocs and arms race nor engage in
military expansion," he said.
</P>
<P>
China's development will not pose a threat to any other
country, and the so-called "China threat" is entirely unfounded
and fabricated with ulterior motives, he said.
</P>
<P>
On China's role in safeguarding world peace, Tang said, "China
is a staunch force for the maintenance of world peace and regional
stability. It is our consistent view that state-to-state relations
should be handled in a spirit of mutual respect and peaceful
coexistence, transcending the differences in social system and
ideology."
</P>
<P>
Countries should safeguard their own interests and, at the same
time, respect those of others and continuously expand mutually
beneficial cooperation through seeking the convergent points of
common interests, he said.
</P>
<P>
"With regard to the existing differences and disputes, it is
necessary to persist in dialogue, not engage in confrontation and
to strive to settle them by peaceful means rather than by
resorting to force or threat of force," he said. "It is essential
to completely reject cold-war mentality, advocate a new security
concept and resolve international and regional security issues
through consensus and participation on an equal footing."
</P>
<P>
"We in China stand for the equality of all countries, big or
small, and accelerated democratization of international
relations," he said. "World affairs should be handled through
consultation by all countries, and no country should impose its
own will on others." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM on World's Peace, Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government
would, as always, support the Middle East peace process and the
efforts made by the United Nations and the relevant parties to
this end, China said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd Session of the General Assembly, Chinese
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan said the Middle East peace process
had been in a stalemate for some time, which had aroused extensive
concern in the international community.
</P>
<P>
Tang said China was of the view that the Arab nations and
Israel should hold negotiations in an earnest and pragmatic manner
so as to achieve a comprehensive, just and lasting peace, which
would be not only in the fundamental interests of the Arab and
Israeli people, but also conducive to world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Tang expressed the hope that all the parties concerned in the
Arab-Israeli disputes would take a flexible and pragmatic position
to promote constant progress of the peace negotiations under the
principle of "land for peace" and on the basis of the relevant
U.N. resolutions and the agreements already reached.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister said China was following the
developments in the Kosovo region in Yugoslavia with concern, and
it was China's hope that the parties involved would solve the
problem through political dialogues.
</P>
<P>
Tang said the sovereignty and territorial integrity of
Yugoslavia should be respected.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said the border conflicts between Ethiopia
and Eritrea and the conflict in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo were another source of China's concern.
</P>
<P>
Tang expressed the hope they would be appropriately resolved by
the parties involved through peaceful means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
