<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-23 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Syria has given Lebanese companies a discount of
about 70 percent on the cost of advertizing their products in the
state-controlled Syrian media, local newspapers reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This decision means that Lebanese industrialists, merchants and
heads of tourism, hotel and service companies could advertize in
the Syrian media with less than a third of the cost they had to
pay previously.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese businessmen said the decision gave the expensive
Lebanese products marketing tools to compete with cheaper locally
made Syrian products.
</P>
<P>
In last March, the two countries agreed to abolish customs
duties on locally made products for four years starting in 1999.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Medgulf Strikers, one of the top 10 insurance
companies in Lebanon, has agreed to merge with Arab Universal,
another large firm ultimately by Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's The Daily Star newspaper said that the new company,
valued at 30 million U.S. dollars, would constitute the biggest
insurance group in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The two companies have now an estimated 120,000 clients, it
added.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Minister of Industries Gholamreza Shafei
announced on Wednesday that Iran is now producing pesticide
spraying planes.
</P>
<P>
Iran is among the top 20 countries of the world which are
active in producing these types of planes, he said, but giving no
more information.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran recorded a 2.9 percent growth in its gross
domestic product (GDP) in the past Iranian year (ending on March
20), the official news agency IRNA reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Central Bank of Iran (CBI) Mohsen Nourbakhsh
announced the figure in a CBI meeting on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the revenue from oil and gas exports showed a 20.5
percent decline in the year compared to the preceding year's
figure, Nourbakhsh said.
</P>
<P>
He put the incomes from oil exports at 15.5 billion
U.S. dollars last Iranian year, showing 19.8 percent decline from
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
He said the share of oil in the government's general incomes
decreased to 41.6 percent in last Iranian year from 57.4 percent in
the preceding year.
</P>
<P>
However, Nourbakhsh said, the speedy growth in tax incomes
compensated the drop in oil incomes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
