<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austrian Minister on Cooperation With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia should revive its
prerequisites for foreign cooperation if the European Union is
interested in cooperation with Russia, Austrian Finance Minister
Rudolf Edlinger said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Austrian minister Wednesday met with officials
from the Russian government, the Central Bank and the State Duma,
or lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Edlinger told a briefing that the August 17 unilateral actions
of the Russian authorities undermined trust in Russia, so the
restoration of this trust is an important objective.
</P>
<P>
According to him, his meeting with the Russian officials was
focused on the budget, inflation control and forced recovery of
the banking system in the country.
</P>
<P>
He said that though Russia has not worked out yet a finalized
anti-crisis program, the West is convinced that "this government
will follow the path for the development of a social market
economy."
</P>
<P>
Edlinger believed that the present Russian government differs
from the previous one in its ability to rely on broad support from
the State Duma. It can count on the approval of tax reforms, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the question whether Russia would get new loans, he said
"the issue of tranches will depend on how market reforms are
carried out."
</P>
<P>
The minister said further aid is a subject for negotiations and
an appropriate budget, tax and social policy is necessary for a
decision. 
</P>
</TEXT>
