<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM on U.N. Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- It was necessary to
carry out appropriate reform of the United Nations so that it
could better keep abreast of the changing situation and serve its
member states, China said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd Session of the General Assembly, Chinese
Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan said some reform measures and
recommendations proposed by the U.N. secretary-general had been
approved by the General Assembly and were now being put into
practice.
</P>
<P>
Tang said reform of the Security Council had been under intense
discussions and there were still differences among member states,
and China hoped that all parties would adopt a constructive
approach and take an active part in the relevant consultations
with a view to reaching a proper settlement of relevant issues.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese foreign minister said the reform of the Security
Council bore on the interests of all countries and so required a
democratic style of work and extensive and full consultations, and
all the member states should have equal right to speak on the
question of the reform and their reasonable proposals should be
reflected to the full.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council was not a club of rich countries and the
purpose of its reform was not just to meet the concerns of only a
few big countries, said Tang, adding more attention should be
given to the interests and aspirations of the vast numbers of
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Tang said the reform measures were something of major
significance as they bore on enhancing the role of the Security
Council in maintaining international peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The measures should be worked out on the basis of the realities
and in consideration of history, and in order to ensure the
reformed Security Council gain extensive support from the member
states, it was essential to adhere to the principle of consensus,
Tang stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Plans Further Cocoa Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Ghana has set up a task force
to study production boosting reforms in the cocoa sector, a
report from Accra, capital of Ghana, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The task force of four working groups, installed by Finance
Minister Kwame Peprah, will look at ways of boosting annual
production to around 450,000 tons, the level attained following
independence from Britain in the 1960s, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"It is the task of each (working) group to...suggest
appropriate policy, institutional and investment measures needed
to address and improve Ghana's competitive edge," Peprah said.
</P>
<P>
The task force, chaired by Deputy Finance Minister Victor
Selormey, will deal with production, marketing, processing and
quality, infrastructure and finance, taxation and pricing policy.
</P>
<P>
Ghana started reforming its cocoa sector 10 years ago. Annual
production is between 350,000 and 400,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
"The reforms have often occurred piecemeal at different times
and under different covenants resulting in the implementation of
conflicting policies," Peprah said.
</P>
<P>
Yields per hectare in Ghana are low at 0.2 tons, against 0.3
to 0.5 tons in neighboring Cote d'Iovire, the world's largest
cocoa producer with total production of over one million tons.
</P>
<P>
Production in Ghana is low because farmers lack sufficient
incentives to work their farms and cannot afford inputs, industry
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Pesticide shortage were a major factor in the decline of
Ghana's cocoa production during the 1970s and early 1980s, when
production fell below 200,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Ghana's farmers get 56 percent of the FOB (free on board)
price, one of the lowest in the world.
</P>
<P>
The state Cocoa Marketing Board (COCOBOD) has introduced a
credit scheme for farmers to increase pesticide use and plans to
raise the farmgate price to 60 percent of FOB by 2000, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Ghana, however, has no intention of liberalizing the sector
completely, unlike Cote d'Ivoire, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Ghana has eased state control by allowing private buyers to
take 30 percent of farm purchases. COCOBOD takes the rest and
keeps a monopoly over exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
