<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Forces Secure Vital Positions in Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A regional task force
secured several strategic positions in Lesotho by Wednesday
afternoon, but law and order still had to be restored in Maseru,
the South African National Defense Force (SANDF) said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Strategic points secured by Wednesday included Katse Dam and
two military bases, where dissident Lesotho soldiers put up
fierce resistance against peacekeeping soldiers from South Africa
and Botswana, South African Press Association quoted the SANDF
statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The SANDF said rebel Lesotho soldiers suffered about 20
casualties in skirmishes at the dam on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mopping-up operations continued at Makonyane military base
outside Maseru and the area was being swept for dissidents. Many
weapons, including anti-aircraft guns, were seized at the base.
</P>
<P>
By Wednesday afternoon soldiers from South Africa and Botswana
also secured the airport at Maseru, but it was not yet in
operation because of staff problems.
</P>
<P>
"The objective is to get the airport functioning as soon as
possible," the SANDF said.
</P>
<P>
The radio station in Maseru was being brought back on the air,
and its staff would be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
While the central business district of the capital was safe,
some criminal activity still existed.
</P>
<P>
Retracting earlier reports that nine South Africans were
killed in clashes with rebel Lesotho soldiers, the SANDF said:
"The casuality figure is now confirmed at eight dead and 17
wounded."
</P>
<P>
The task force entered Lesotho in the early hours of Tuesday
under the auspices of the Southern African Development Community
to quell rising unrest over perceived irregularities in the May
23 general elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
