<HEADLINE> Uganda's Fight Against AIDS Bearing Fruits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan government's
approach to AIDS problem is bearing good results, President
Yoweri Museveni said at a meeting with the visiting
British Princess Royal, Princess Anne, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president briefed the British royal member about Uganda's
AIDS Program, saying that the entire Ugandan population are
aware of the dangers of the virus.
</P>
<P>
Their talks focused on humanitarian and social welfare in
Uganda and in the region, a press release from the President's
Office said Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
President Museveni expressed gratitude to the British
government for its support in helping Uganda fight the terminal
disease, especially for the newly-constructed Mildmay Center
which will be dedicated to caring for people with AIDS.
</P>
<P>
They also discussed the regional insecurity and issues
concerning refugees in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said that Uganda will improve the
infrastructure to improve food distribution to those affected by
instability.
</P>
<P>
The British princess arrived here Tuesday for a four-day
official visit. This is Princess Anne's second visit to Uganda.
Her first visit was in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
