<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Economy Still in Good Shape: Thiessen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian economy is still
in good shape despite the ongoing global uncertainty and
pressures, Gordon Thiessen, governor of the Bank of Canada, said
Wednesday in Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came in a speech to the Board of Trade in St.
John's, where the Bank of Canada's Board of Directors is meeting.
</P>
<P>
"Although Canadians have to deal with these difficulties coming
from abroad, it is important to remember that, overall, our
economy is still in good shape," Thiessen said.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We now have a low rate of inflation, a fiscal
surplus, and a declining public debt-to-GDP ratio. As well,
Canadians businesses have undertaken major restructuring and
investment initiatives to increase their productivity."
</P>
<P>
"Because of these fundamental strengths, we are now better
positioned to weather sudden shocks," said the governor of
Canada's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Thiessen said that this year the Canadian economy will not
repeat the 4 percent growth experienced last year. but it may
still expand by two and half to 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The latest indicators suggest continued expansion in consumer
spending and business investment, supported by higher employment
and low medium- and long-term interest rates, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
