<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 1955GMT, September 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Secretary General of the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC) Ezzidine Laraki said on Wednesday that Islamic
countries are coordinating stances on issues raised at the ongoing
53rd United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Egypt's Sawt al Arab (Voice of
Arab) radio from Moroccan capital Rabat before he flew to New
York, Laraki said that Islamic countries' foreign ministers will
hold a meeting late this week for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
The OIC is concerned with the Middle East peace process, the
Afghan situations and other regional and international issues, he
said. (Egypt-OIC-Coordination)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami said here on
Wednesday that Iran expects a peaceful solution to the Afghan
issue.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon return from the 53rd United Nations General
Assembly, Khatami said that Tehran does not welcome war, the
official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that Afghan issue was one of the most important issues
discussed at the 53rd session of the U.N. General Assembly and the
U.N. would send a team to Afghanistan to probe into the crimes
committed by the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team would also investigate the issue of killing eight
Iranian diplomats and a reporter by the Taliban forces in Mazari
Sharif, northern Afghanistan, Khatami said.
</P>
<P>
However, he reiterated that Iran reserves the right to defend
itself, the official news agency IRNA reported.
(Iran-Khatami-Afghan Issue)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- U.S. ambassador to Kuwait James Larocco said
Wednesday that Iraq's non-cooperation with the United Nations will
not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) quoted Larocco as saying "the
non-cooperation of the Iraqi regime has been happening for quite a
long time. This is something we are vigilant about all the time."
</P>
<P>
This move will not be tolerated, "not now or in the future," he
stressed. (Kuwait-US Ambassador-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cypriot government has outrightly rejected a
proposal from the Turkish Cypriot side for examining the disputes
over property rights in Cyprus which resulted from the Turkish
military intervention in 1974.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement released here Wednesday, Cypriot
government spokesman Christos Stylianides said "there is no
Security Council resolution or decision by the Human Rights Court
which refers to exchange of property, as the Turkish side
proposes."
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash proposed Tuesday that an
independent, autonomous commission be set up to identify formulae
and criteria concerning property between the two sides.
(Cyprus-Turkish Cypriots-Property) 
</P>
</TEXT>
