<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan PMs Open Talks in New York </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The prime ministers of India
and Pakistan met here Wednesday to tackle some of the pressing
issues such as Kashmir and the nuclear race which are affecting
the ties between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued before their luncheon talks in a New
York hotel said Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajipayee and
his Pakistani counterpart, Nawaz Sharif, would discuss all issues
and review developments in South Asia in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
But the most eye-catching are the long-standing dispute over
Kashmir which has recently been intensified and the situation
following the nuclear tests by the two countries in May, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is their second since their nuclear tests induced
international condemnations compounded with demand for their
signing of the nuclear test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
They met for the first time during a South Asian Summit in
July. Progress has since been reported in contacts between their
foreign secretaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
