<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans to Increase Defense Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Warned by the Pentagon
leaders about eroding military readiness, U.S. President Bill
Clinton planned to increase the nation's military expenditure by
billions of U.S. dollars by 2000.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Defense Secretary William Cohen Tuesday, Clinton
called for immediate relief in the form of a supplemental
appropriation for 1999 to address shortages in spare parts, Navy
recruitment, Army training and other accounts related to the
ability of U.S. forces to conduct operations.
</P>
<P>
"Although we have done much to support readiness, more needs to
be done," Clinton said in the letter, which was disclosed by The
Washington Post and The New York Times Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Post quoted a senior defense official as saying that it was
likely that 1 billion dollars will be added to the 4 billion
dollars already before Congress in the requested increase in the
budget to cover the extended Bosnia mission, Year 2000 computer
fixes and other items.
</P>
<P>
It would be the first major boost in military spending since
Clinton took office.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement with Congress to balance the federal budget,
fiscal 2000 defense spending is currently scheduled to grow
slightly to 276 billion dollars. The agreement prevents any real
growth in annual defense spending.
</P>
<P>
Republicans in Congress say the figure is inadequate on the
heels of a decade of military spending cuts by the world's only
remaining superpower.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon officials had not worked out the final 2000 budget.
But military officials estimated that the military would need 10
billion dollars to 20 billion dollars annually to shore up
military readiness.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Clinton discussed military readiness and funding
with the nation's top generals and admirals and vowed to ensure
that U.S. armed forces will "dominate the battlefields of the
future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
