<HEADLINE> UK's Tobacco Industry Challenges EU Ad Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Britain's biggest tobacco
companies have begun a legal bid to overturn the European Union's
ban on advertising their products.
</P>
<P>
Under the new law passed last December, cinema and billboard
advertising will be banned after three years and newspaper
advertisements a year after that. All tobacco advertising and
sponsorship of events like Formula One racing will be banned by
the year 2006.
</P>
<P>
British American Tobacco, Gallaher, Imperial and Rothmans say
the European Community has overstretched its legal powers,
according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
They are arguing that, under the EU's founding treaties, public
health policy is not defined as an area for collective
decision-making between the EU's member states.
</P>
<P>
A separate appeal by the German Government is expected to
follow a similar argument.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco companies launched their action at the High Court
in London on Tuesday and are seeking to have the matter referred
to the European Court.
</P>
<P>
David Swan, chief executive of the Tobacco Manufacturers'
Association, was quoted by local media as saying that "The tobacco
industry, like any other business is entitled to basic legal
rights.
</P>
<P>
"The directive will severely restrict the companies' ability to
tell customers about their products and could even rule out
providing information on tobacco products to adult smokers who
request it," he said. "This is totally unjustified and we will
vigorously challenge the basis on which these restrictions to a
legal product are being introduced."
</P>
<P>
Only 11 of the 15 European Union member countries voted for the
ban to be introduced. This is the smallest number possible for a
proposal to become law. However, the European Commission says it
is confident it could successfully defend its position.
</P>
<P>
"Our legal advice is that we are on solid ground," Barbara
Nolan, a spokeswoman for the EU's executive body, was quoted as
saying. "We are confident that we can defend any legal challenge
to the directive." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
