<HEADLINE> Tanzania Hopes to Attract More U.S. Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania plans to attract
more American tourists despite the August 7 terrorist attack on
the U.S. embassy here, a Tanzanian tourism official said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Following a successful marketing campaign by the Tanzania
Tourist Board (TTB) in the United States, the number of tourists
from Canada and United States is expected to surpass the targeted
40,000 by the end of this year, said the agency's information
officer, Johnson Manase.
</P>
<P>
Manase said that TTB's publicity campaign prior to the opening
of the American Travel Market Exhibition held in mid-September in
Orlando, U.S., made more Americans know Tanzania's tourist
attractions.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister of Tourism and Natural Resources, Zakia
Meghji, helped to build up the east African country's image by
delivering a televised speech in the United States, said Manase.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition drew nearly 3,000 U.S. travel company owners,
agents and tour operators. Tanzania was represented by 21
companies, most of which are privately owned except the
state-owned TTB.
</P>
<P>
The horrible bombing at the U.S. Embassy in Dar es Salaam has
brought people of the two countries even closer, Manase said,
adding that a visit by U.S. Secretary of Commerce William Daley
last week further cemented the ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It is high time for Tanzania to make more efforts in
attracting more tourists as Tanzania is endowed with abundant
tourism attractions such as vast wildlife reserves and Mount
Kilimanjaro, he said.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has improved its infrastructures a lot, like the
rehabilitation of the Makuyuni road leading to the world-famous
Ngorongoro Crater. The road was damaged by El Nino-charged
rains.
</P>
<P>
The country has also built more tourist hotels, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The peace prevails in the country is another asset for
tourist business." said the official.
</P>
<P>
Tourist arrivals in Tanzania last year reached 359,000 with
10 percent of them from the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
