<HEADLINE> U.S. Fed Gives Green-Light to Citicorp-Travelers Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Federal Reserve Board
Wednesday approved the mega-merger of Citicorp and Travelers Group
Inc., and the two New York-based companies are renamed as the
Citigroup Inc.
</P>
<P>
The combination could offer consumers one-stop financing
shopping for everything from credit cards and checking to
insurance and investing.
</P>
<P>
The merger which was first announced in April, was passed by a
5-1 vote at a closed meeting of the Fed.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department also gave its green light for the deal
today.
</P>
<P>
"We conducted a thorough investigation. We have closed that
investigation, and we have allowed the transaction to go through,"
said Justice spokeswoman Gina Talamona.
</P>
<P>
Citicorp is the parent company of Citibank, the world's largest
issuer of credit cards with some 60 million in circulation.
Travelers is an insurance, brokerage and investment banking giant
with operating companies bearing household names such as Solomon
Smith Barney, Primerica Financial Services and Travelers Life &AMP;
Annuity.
</P>
<P>
The merged company would continue to use Travelers trademark
red umbrella as part of its logo.
</P>
<P>
With more than 100 million customers worldwide and assets of
more than 751 billion U.S. dollars, Citigroup would be the largest
financial services firm in the United States, able to cross-market
an unusually broad range of financial services to consumers.
</P>
<P>
The recent wave of corporate mergers has swept not only the
financial sector, but included telecommunications corporations,
auto manufacturers and oil companies.
</P>
<P>
The Citicorp-Travelers deal was billed as the largest
combination of companies ever when it was announced last Spring,
at a value of 70 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
