<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Remain Firm on Hope for Rates Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Leading European shares
remained firm on Wednesday as investors took heart from
speculation that U.S. interest rates would be cut at next week's
Federal Reserve policy meeting.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 finished the day 111.4 points higher at
5214.7, just below its interaday peak of 5219.5 hit just before
close.
</P>
<P>
Key support came from the Dow Jones, which was up 85 points on
growing speculation that the Federal Reserve would ease its key
interest rate at next Tuesday's six-weekly policy deliberations.
</P>
<P>
A leading member of central bank hinted on Tuesday that
monetary policy would be eased and investors were eagerly awaiting
Fed chairman Alan Greenspan's testimony to the Senate banking
committee for clues.
</P>
<P>
The hope is that any Fed move will be rapidly followed by one
from the Bank of England.
</P>
<P>
The market has rebounded solidly from Monday's finish below
5000 and volume also improved to around 860m shares by close. But
dealers warned of a lack of sustained upward momentum during
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
They said underlying conditions remained volatile, particularly
amid concerns about the stability of financial markets in Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, German shares hit session highs as Wall Street
pushed ahead. Encouraging corporate news and a stronger dollar
also helped the market. The Xetra Dax finished 173.73 points
higher at 4722.96.
</P>
<P>
"A recovery like this isn't unusual after strong retreats,"
said an equities analyst at a bank in Berlin. Traders said most of
the gains were due to short position covering and to the effect of
institutional investors buying up stocks at bargain prices.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French stocks got a new lease of life as New York
shares bounced back on interest rate speculation. The Cac 40
closed 75.8 points higher at 3423.78.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the Dow's performance helped the market recover
from a mid-session retreat. They said selling in French municipal
services companies Vivendi and Suez Lyonnaise des Eaux over profit
concerns were the main reasons for the retreat. Otherwise, the
market was very calm.  
</P>
</TEXT>
