<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Awards Mandela Gold Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Visiting South African
President Nelson Mandela received the Congressional Gold Medal
Wednesday, becoming the first African awarded the United States'
highest honor.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, 80, is the 100th recipient of the congressional medal,
which was first awarded to Washington in 1776 and since bestowed
on the likes of Lincoln, Winston Churchill and Mother Ther.
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony on the Capital Hill, Mandela, who had led South
Africa's long struggle against apartheid, said he felt "like the
heavyweight boxing champion of the world."
</P>
<P>
"Though we are long past the blaming of our past for our
problems, it does need to be acknowledged that the imbalance and
inequities bequeathed to us by the history of Africa and South
Africa are beyond our capacity to meet on our own," he said.
</P>
<P>
"They call for a partnership of Africa and the United States,
developing and developed countries bringing about a transfer of
resources," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton followed a long lineup of
lawmakers, including House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who beseeched
Americans to follow Mandela's example of humility, sacrifice and
kindness in the face of enmity.
</P>
<P>
"No medal, no award, no fortune, nothing we could give him
could possibly compare to the gifts he has given to us and to the
world," Clinton said before presenting the round gold medal
nestled in a green velvet case.
</P>
<P>
"The only gift that is true recompense is to continue his
mission and to live by the power of his profound and wonderful
example," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela grinned and repeatedly gestured for the assembly of
cheering dignitaries to quiet their standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
The Congress approved the legislation awarding the medal in
July, citing that Mandela has "dedicated his entire life to the
abolition of apartheid... and sacrificed his own personal freedom
for the good of everyone."
</P>
<P>
At a news briefing after the ceremony, Mandela praised
Clinton's efforts to improve race relations in the United States
and bring in blacks, minority groups and the disabled into
government institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
