<HEADLINE> Nigerian Trader With 10 Kg Cocaine Arrested in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Ghanaian customs has
arrested a 34-year-old Nigerian trader at the Kotoka
International Airport as he attempted to smuggle into the country
10 kilograms of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
The Pan African News Agency (PANA) Wednesday quoted Baffour Dwumo,
Acting Head of the Customs Preventive Unit at the airport, as
saying that a preliminary test of the substance the man carried
confirmed that it was cocaine.
</P>
<P>
This was one of the biggest hauls recently seized at the
airport, the official said, stressing that they are always alert
when airlines arrive from the Far East.
</P>
<P>
The intercepted cocaine is worth of 400 million Cedis (about
170,000 U.S. Dollars), PANA said.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian trader, identified as Olley Najeen Animashaun but
with a Sierra Leonean passport, Monday arrived from Thailand on
an Ethiopian Airline flight.
</P>
<P>
He was arrested at the second customs check point when he
tried to bribe officials with 550 U.S. Dollars to allow his
passage, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The cocaine was concealed in false compartments of some bowls
alongside other items including T-shirts, ladies sandals and
children's wear.
</P>
<P>
Animashaun claimed that he was not aware of the contents of
the bowls which were given to him by a Nigerian friend, Akeem
Manoma, in Thailand to Convey to his wife in Accra.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had requested financial assistance from Akeem
to enable him to buy a return ticket to Nigeria after using his
money to buy some items to sell in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Animashaun said Akeem agreed to finance him on condition that
he sent the bowls to his wife whom he was to meet at the airport
in Accra.
</P>
<P>
Asked why he attempted to bribe the officer if he claimed he
had no knowledge of the contents of the bowls, the trader said
that he did so because the customs officer demanded it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
