<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. GDP Growth Slows Down Sharply in Second-quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. economic growth
slowed down sharply in the second quarter of this year, putting an
end to a two-year stretch of robust growth, according to a report
released by the Commerce Department Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) grew at a 1.8 percent annual
rate in the second quarter, after shooting up at a 5.5 percent
rate during the first three months of the year, the department
said.
</P>
<P>
The revised growth was a bit better than the 1.6 percent rate
estimated a month ago and the initial 1.4 percent estimate of two
months ago. Still, it indicated that the U.S. economy has entered
a new phase of moderate growing following nearly a 4 percent
growth rate through 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
The long expansion has reduced the nation's unemployment rate
to near a 28-year low and the recent slowdown hasn't yet greatly
restricted demand for labor.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report today, the Labor Department said that
first-time claims for unemployment fell by 8,000 to a seasonally
adjusted 292,000 last week, the lowest level in five months.
</P>
<P>
In the second quarter, after-tax corporate profits managed a
weak rebound. They rose 0.6 percent from the quarter before to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 481.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Still, that followed back-to-back drops of 1.6 percent in the
first quarter and 3.5 percent in the fourth quarter of last year.
Despite the increase in the second-quarter, profits still were 1.2
percent lower than a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Despite the overall slowdown in the second quarter, growth
remained strong in many areas. Consumer spending grew at a 6.1
percent annual rate and housing construction at a 15 percent
rate. Businesses increased investment in new equipment, including
computers at an 18.8 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
Government spending rose at a 3.7 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
The various changes left the gross domestic product
accumulating at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 8.44 trillion
dollars, in current dollars, during the second quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
