<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Agrees to Prepare for Kosovo Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- NATO issued on Thursday an
activation warning for a limited air strike and a phased air
campaign in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The warning allows NATO to enter into a state of increased
level of military preparedness and to identify the assets required
for the planned military actions, said NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana in issuing the warning.
</P>
<P>
Solana said: "The use of force will require further decision
by the North Atlantic Council.
</P>
<P>
"But the decision is an important political signal of NATO's
readiness to use force if it becomes necessary to do so."
</P>
<P>
He also expressed strong support of the U.N. Security Council
resolution adopted on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
NATO has been studying various options of the use of force in
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo ever since NATO foreign ministers
met in late April.
</P>
<P>
The western military alliance has carried out an air-borne
drill in Albania in mid-June to demonstrate its capability of
rapid deployment into the region.
</P>
<P>
But NATO stopped short of resorting to force in Kosovo after
Russia warned to veto a U.N. resolution that would give NATO the
mandate to intervene in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
NATO has been reviewing the situation in Kosovo on a weekly
basis and a U.S. envoy to Kosovo last week briefed NATO diplomats
on the refugee situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 250,000 refugees are now residing in makeshift
shelters in the forests and mountains in Kosovo as winter is
approaching. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
