<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Household Income Increases, Poverty Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. household income
rose and poverty rates fell in 1997 for the third year running,
the Census Bureau said while releasing its annual income and
poverty report Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, 13.3 percent of Americans lived in poverty, down from
13.7 percent in 1996, a decline led by blacks and Hispanics,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The number of poor blacks dropped by 600,000 to 9.1 million,
although more than one in four blacks still live in poverty. For
Hispanics, the poverty rate dropped to 27.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Poverty also declined in big cities, from 19.6 percent in 1996
to 18.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Eleven percent of white Americans live in poverty. The gap
between the wealthiest and poorest Americans remained the same
between 1996 and 1997. The difference between men's and women's
earnings also kept the same. Women continued to earn 74 cents for
every dollar for men.
</P>
<P>
The median household income for all Americans in 1997 rose 1.9
percent to 37,005 U.S. dollars, not statistically different from
the peak in 1989, before the nation fell into recession.
</P>
<P>
Twelve states saw real median income levels rise while four saw
drops.
</P>
<P>
States seeing rises, using two-year averages, were Alabama,
Delaware, Indiana, Kansas, Louisiana, New Mexico, North Caroline,
Oklahoma, South Carolina, Utah, Virginia and Washington. Income
fell in Hawaii, Iowa, Maine and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
Alaska had the highest median household income at 50,829
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The poverty rate dropped in three states, Alabama, Mississippi
and South Carolina but increased in Arkansas and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
Nationwide, 35.6 million people lived in poverty. Last year, a
family of four was considered poor if its annual income was 16,400
dollars or less. For a family of three, the poverty threshold was
12,802 dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
