<HEADLINE> Primakov Defines Pressing Tasks of Russian Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The new Russian government is
getting down to business to solve the country's key problems,
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said at a cabinet meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Primakov defined his cabinet's most pressing tasks as reviving
the banking system, balancing the budget, and laying a foundation
for paying wages, pensions and allowances on timely basis.
</P>
<P>
As reported by the Interfax news agency, he pledged that
workers and retirees will get their wages and pensions on time
from October on, and begin to get their overdued salaries.
</P>
<P>
The government will also give Russian citizens monthly
subsidies from early 1999 on to ease their suffering from ruble's
devaluation and inflation, said the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
As the administrative measures were "insufficient" to balance
the federal budget, economic measures such as increasing taxes are
likely to be taken, he said.
</P>
<P>
But he also indicated that his cabinet will work to reduce the
tax burden on manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Primakov criticized the financial decisions by the Kiriyenko
cabiet on August 17, saying those rashly made decisions had
plunged Russian financial and industrial sectors into chaos.
</P>
<P>
The decisions were not authorized by President Boris Yeltsin,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
