<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Cities to Get U.N. Grants for Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. office in Nairobi
announced Thursday that the U.N. Foundations Inc. has approved to
allocate 2.27 million U.S. Dollars for improving water management
in ten African cities.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Environment Program (UNEP)and the U.N. Center for
Human Settlements (Habitat) based in the capital of Kenya will
receive the funding for their joint project aimed at helping
Africa to deal with the growing water crisis in cities.
</P>
<P>
"Africa, water, urban issues -- these are priority areas of
concern for UNEP and Habitat," said Klaus Topfer, Executive
Director of the UNEP and Habitat, at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Among the ten cities are Nairobi (Kenya), Dar es Salaam
(Tanzania), Kampala (Uganda), Johannesburg (South Africa), Cairo
(Egypt), Tunis (Tunisia), Dakar (Senegal), Ibadan (Nigeria),
Harare (Zimbabwe) and Gaborone (Botswana).
</P>
<P>
The 50-month project, called "Managing Water for African
Cities", will assist African countries to put in place early
warning mechanisms for timely detection of potential "hot spots",
where sustainability is threatened.
</P>
<P>
There are two focuses in the project -- the water demand in
cities and mitigating the impact of urbanization on fresh water
resources and aquatic ecosystems.
</P>
<P>
It will be first comprehensive initiative to support African
countries to improve urban water management and protect the
continent's threatened water resources and aquatic ecosystems
from urban pollutions.
</P>
<P>
Topfer also announced that the U.N. Foundation Inc, also known
as the Turner Foundation, has granted 650,000 Dollars for
projects to reduce the impact of El Nino weather phenomenon which
causes mass environmental devastation across the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
