<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot Government: Confederation Not in Line With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot government spokesman
Christos Stylianides said Thursday that a proposal put forward by
Turkish Cypriots for a confederation of two states in Cyprus is
not in line with U.N. resolutions and international law.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting in New York on recent statements by Turkish
Foreign Minister Ismail Cem that Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash's proposal promotes the unity of Cyprus and is in line
with U.N. resolutions on Cyprus, Cyprus News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"It seems as if Mr. Cem has his own way of interpreting things
or (he) does not know how to read very well known words used in
international law which are common sense," Stylianides said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Denktash's proposal "is contrary to
U.N. resolutions, which is why all permanent members of the
Security Council rejected it."
</P>
<P>
Denktash made the proposal last month, which he claimed as
"the only structure" to safeguard the security, identity and
well-being of Greek and Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolutions on Cyprus call for the establishment of a
bicommunal, bizonal federation with a single international
personality and citizenship.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said that if the Turkish foreign minister believes
the proposal is in line with U.N. resolutions, he is completely
"irrational," because the resolutions stipulate for Cyprus'
independence, unity and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
"Denktash's proposal refers to two protectorates (of Greece
and Turkey) and leads to the division of Cyprus," the spokesman
stressed.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to help reunify Cyprus
under the bizonal, bicommunal federation formula, but no tangible
results have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
