<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia in Efforts to Move into Information Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad Thursday urged his countrymen to adjust and take
advantage of the phenomenal development in information technology
in the country's efforts to move into the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
Chairing a meeting of the National Information Technology
Council (NITC) here, Mahathir said: "The sudden upsurge of
information and communication technologies is changing the way in
which business is done and industry behaves. We have to adjust and
take advantage of this phenomenal development."
</P>
<P>
In a report presented at the meeting, he said Malaysians will
have to adjust and take advantage of the phenomenal development in
information technology as the country's industrialization strategy
alone is not going to help it achieve a fully-developed nation
status by 2020.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the businesses' very success hinges on their
ability to get into shape for the global game of electronic
business.
</P>
<P>
In its effort to move Malaysia into the Information Age, the
NITC has a critical role to play in managing the country's
transformation to a knowledge-rich society, Mahathir said, urging
the NITC to keep in mind the need to preserve and strengthen the
intrinsic Asian values.
</P>
<P>
The key issues to be considered by the NITC over the next few
years are the role of the government and the private and voluntary
sectors, the need to ensure universal access to information, the
development of technological competence and ways to facilitate
electronic commerce, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over the next decade, he said, one of the most important tasks
is to make sure that the benefits of network computing are made
available to every Malaysian, and to schools, hospitals, clinics
and voluntary organizations as well as businesses.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has made the first important move towards the
Information Age by creating a Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC),
where a fully networked federal government administrative center
-- Putrajaya, will be completed in 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
