<HEADLINE> Customs Sector Urged to Curb Staff Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Senior Chinese offcial Wu Yi
has called on customs departments to educate staffers
of the need to curb internal corruption in order to ensure the
success of the ongoing anti-smuggling campaign.
</P>
<P>
State councillor Wu issued the call during a national
conference on combating corruption amongst custom officers. The
conference was held in Beijing on Tuesday and Wednesday this week.
</P>
<P>
Participants discussed a case of the customs department under
the Futian Bonded Zone Customs Office in east China's Fujian
Province.
</P>
<P>
Wu urged customs departments to fully implement the ongoing
anti-smuggling drive launched by the central leadership in order
to effectively reduce smuggling.
</P>
<P>
She said the campaign has greatly improved domestic markets of
petroleum products, edible oils, chemical fertilizers and chemical
fibers.
</P>
<P>
Wu thanked customs departments for their contribution to the
battle against smuggling, but pointed out that problems still
exist in some departments with unscrupulous staffers who abuse their
official power for personal gain from smugglers.
</P>
<P>
The customs sector should improve internal management, said Wu,
adding that individuals abetting smuggling must severely be
punished.
</P>
<P>
Customs departments should adopt democratic practice in order
to eradicate corrupt behavior, said Wu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
