<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kohl's Junior Partner Warns Against Grand Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The small Free Democratic Party
(FDP) in German Chancellor Helmut Kohl's ruling coalition Thursday
warned its big partners against allying with the main opposition
party -- the Social Democratic Party (SPD).
</P>
<P>
With national election three days away, FDP leader Wolfgang
Gerhardt told reporters in Bonn any possible grand coalition with
the SPD would only benefit the latter.
</P>
<P>
Germany is governed by a coalition of three parties --
the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), the Christian Social Union
(CSU) and the FDP. The coalition ruled the former West Germany
from October 1982 through unification.
</P>
<P>
Gerhardt's warning came after Kohl said Wednesday for the first
time that it was possible in theory for the country's two largest
political parties, his CDU and the SPD to form a grand coalition
government after the election.
</P>
<P>
Although Kohl said he was still against such an idea and would
not take part in such a coalition, his younger allies in the CDU
are less unequivocal.
</P>
<P>
The SPD was currently in a "strategic quandary" because of
voters' concern about their possible alliance with the ecologist
Greens party, Gerhardt said, adding that Kohl's CDU should not
help the SPD out of the dilemma by discussing a grand coalition.
</P>
<P>
The grand coalition option is at the center of political
considerations now in Bonn because many polling institutes predict
that as the election race tends to be a extremely tight one at its
final stage, it is likely that neither the CDU nor the SPD would
be able to muster a majority in parliament even in alliance with
their respective partners, the FDP and the Greens.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's challenger, the SPD chancellor candidate Gerhard
Schroeder has never ruled out the possibility of such a grand
coalition. Analysts believe that it is a strategy of Schroeder to
reassure middle-of-the-road voters alarmed by the Greens' radical
demands such as a call to triple the gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
The biggest victims of a grand coalition between the CDU and
SPD would be the FDP, which has been in every German government for
nearly 30 years, as well as the Greens, who are hoping to come to
power in Bonn for the first time as the junior partner in a
so-call "Red-Green Coalition" with the SPD. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
