<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burtenshaw Fined after 'Bungs' Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Former Arsenal chief scout
Steve Burtenshaw was fined by the Football Association on
Thursday for accepting an illegal payment as part of a transfer
deal.
</P>
<P>
Burtenshaw, now chief scout at First Division Queen's Park Ran
gers, was fined 7,500 pounds and ordered to pay 2,500 pounds
costs after admitting misconduct at a hearing last week.
</P>
<P>
He received 35,000 pounds from football agent Rune Hauge
following Danish midfielder John Jensen's move from Brondby to
Arsenal six years ago.
</P>
<P>
But his solicitors claim the fine is "unduly severe" and they
are considering an appeal.
</P>
<P>
An FA statement said: "The payment was a contravention of FA
rules and was a clear conflict of interest with his club.
</P>
<P>
"It was accepted by the commission that the payment was not
solicited by Burtenshaw. However, the payment of back-handers to
management, with or without their knowledge, is unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Burtenshaw told the hearing he had made a careless error of
judgment and was deeply sorry.
</P>
<P>
And his solicitors, Burton Copeland, said the FA statement did
not reflect the agreed facts that Burtenshaw had at no time
expected to receive any payment for the transfer.
</P>
<P>
Their statement said: "Mr. Burtenshaw volunteered the
information both to Arsenal when the inquiries were first made
and to the relevant authorities which led to the bringing of the
proceedings. He has co-operated fully with the all the various
inquiries over the years."
</P>
<P>
Former Arsenal manager George Graham, now in charge at Leeds, s
erved a one-year ban from the game as part of the so-called
'bungs' (unauthorized payment) inquiry.
</P>
<P>
An inquiry by the FA into the transfers of Dane Jensen and
Norwegian Pal Lydersen to Arsenal found Graham guilty of
accepting 425,000 pounds in illegal payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
