<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Fund Reconstruction in Flooded Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China's four largest
commercial banks are actively assisting the efforts of
flood-ravaged provinces to restore normal life and industrial
production.
</P>
<P>
The banks -- Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC),
Agricultural Bank of China (ABC), Bank of China (BOC) and China
Construction Bank (CCB) -- are the country's only four state-owned
commercial banking institutions.
</P>
<P>
ICBC has granted 2.2 billion yuan in loans for various projects
in Hunan, Hubei, Jiangxi, Heilongjiang and Jilin provinces.
</P>
<P>
The BOC has dispatched a high-ranking fact-finding team, led by
the BOC President Wang Xuebing, to Hunan and Hubei provinces,
areas suffering the greatest devastation during summer flooding.
</P>
<P>
The BOC has pledged to loan 7.65 billion yuan for restoration
projects in the two provinces, and will provide additional funds
for infrastructure construction projects.
</P>
<P>
The ABC, on the other hand, has focused helping homeless
villagers rebuild their homes.
</P>
<P>
The Hubei Branch of the CCB has granted loans of over 700
million yuan to local flood victims. The CCB's Beijing
headquarters is currently considering a plan to allow branches in
other flood-ravaged provinces to grant additional loans totalling
700 million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
