<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt will lift the export average index price of
crude oil for October to 1.70 dollars less than the Brent price
per barrel, Egyptian Arabic daily Alam Al Yom reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The current price for Suez crude is 1.85 dollars less than the
Brent price per barrel, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- France will help develop Iraq's poultry breeding and
provide it with advanced agricultural machinery, Iraqi local press
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Undersecretary of State for Agriculture Bassil Kamel has
disclosed that a French delegation will visit Baghdad soon to
discuss providing Iraq with some 50,000 eggs of high quality to
increase the volume of poultry meat.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian Arab Investment Bank earned 1 million dinars
(1.4 million U.S. dollars) in profits during the first 6 months of
this year, equal to the figure in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
But the total value of the bank's assets increased to 333
million dollars by the end of June of this year from 314 million
dollars a year earlier, the Arabic Alam Al Yom said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- The Algerian airways has signed an agreement with
the royal Jordanian carrier to start a weekly direct flight from
Amman to Algiers in the fourth quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The official Algerian news agency said the deal is absolutely
commercial.
</P>
<P>
The agreement envisages cooperation in maintenance, reciprocal
use of equipment and exchange of technicians.
</P>
<P>
The current link between the capitals of the two countries is a
weekly flight of the Algerian airways between Sharja in the United
Arab Emirates and Algiers via Amman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
