<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FA Cup Final Replays Scrapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The replay rule of English FA
Cup came to an end since this season.
</P>
<P>
This season's final at Wembley will be the first to be decided
on penalties -- the first time in the competition's 127-year
history, if the match fails to produce a winner after 90 minutes
plus extra time.
</P>
<P>
The move brings the FA Cup final into line with all other
major football tournaments, including major European competitions
and the World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
There have been 14 replays needed in the previous 117 finals,
the most recent five years ago when Arsenal beat Sheffield
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
FA spokesman Steve Double said on Thursday: "It has become
clear over recent years that fans going to Wembley would prefer
to have a decision, for better or worse, on the day. There is
also the issue of fixture congestion."
</P>
<P>
The European Champions League final takes place just four days
after this season's FA Cup final on May 22, and it is possible
that Arsenal or Manchester United could be involved in both.
</P>
<P>
Football Supporters Association chairman Graham Bean applauded
the change, saying that "common sense" had prevailed.
</P>
<P>
He added: "There is some tradition in having a cup replay but
in this day and age you have to look at the cost of traveling
down to Wembley and paying for tickets.
</P>
<P>
"We all want our clubs to do well in Europe, irrespective of
which club we support, and anything to help them has to be
welcomed." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
