<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, Guangdong Officials Reach Consensus on Six Items of Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from Hong
Kong and Guangdong province reached consensus on six items of
cooperation between the two sides at the second meeting of the
Hong Kong/Guangdong Cooperation Joint Conference held here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The two delegations are led by Administrative Secretary Anson
Chan of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) and Vice
Governor Wang Qishan of the Guangdong Provincial Government
respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides reached agreement on linking
up the information networks between HK and Guangdong; improving
the management of land crossings; cooperation between the two
sides in boosting tourism; furthering cross-boundary cooperation
on environmental protection; improving the business environment
in Guangdong; and Hong Kong-Guangdong technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to set up an exclusive electronic network
between HKSAR Government and the Guangdong Provincial Government.
Both governments can browse information and exchange electronic
mails on the exclusive network.
</P>
<P>
A Hong Kong/Guangdong expert group on information technology
has been set up by the two sides to coordinate the project and
monitor the progress. This group will further study and draw up
plans for cooperation over information technology.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to implement two measures to improve the
management of land crossings and to ease the growing
cross-boundary traffic flow -- extending the opening hours of the
existing four land crossings and allowing goods vehicles to freely
select the crossing points for entry and exit by phases.
</P>
<P>
An expert group has been set up to study ways to further
enhance cooperation between the two sides in promoting tourism.
</P>
<P>
The group agreed to broaden the scope of work of the existing
"Pearl River Delta Tourism Promotion Organization" and to widen
the extent of cooperation of this organization. Five measures have
been agreed upon to promote tourism of both places.
</P>
<P>
The two sides acknowledged that the two governments attached
importance to environmental protection and expressed their
determination to enhance cooperation in this area.
</P>
<P>
Through the Hong Kong/Guangdong Cooperation Joint Conference,
both governments will work closely together to tackle
cross-boundary environmental issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Both parties endorsed a cooperation declaration and agreed to
carry out environmental protection work in four areas and devoted
their efforts to protect the natural and ecological resources in
the Deep Bay, Mirs Bay and Pearl River Delta Region.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to examine ways to better the business
environment for Hong Kong businessmen with investment in
Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to examine ways to promote technological
cooperation. A brainstorming group is expected to be set up to
explore areas for long-term items of cooperation for discussion by
the Joint Conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference unanimously came to the view that under the
principle of "One Country, Two Systems" and mutual benefit, the
two sides can, on the basis of the present cooperation, seek a
broader and higher level of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
HKSAR Financial Secretary Donald Tsang and Zhang Liangdong,
director of the Hong Kong Economic Affairs Department of the Hong
Kong and Macao Affairs Office of the State Council, also attended
the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
