<HEADLINE> Taliban Leader Rejects Broad-Based Government Idea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Taliban leader Mulla Umar
has said Afghans have never accepted any government forcibly
imposed on them from abroad during the course of history.
</P>
<P>
Umar made the remarks in the Afghan city of Kandahar in
response to a six plus two meeting (six neighboring countries of
Afghanistan plus the U.S. and Russia) in New York, according to a
report reaching here Thursday from Kabul.
</P>
<P>
The six plus two meeting has decided to send a mission to the
region to assess the possibilities of the formation of a
broad-based government in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Umar was quoted as saying that Afghanistan has its own
religion, culture and social traditions and has the right to form
its own government.
</P>
<P>
He said that Taliban have checked the killing and lawlessness
in Afghanistan but even then are not being recognized by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Umar said that the United Nations does not recognize them but
expects pursuance of international norms and laws from them.
</P>
<P>
The high-level meeting in New York was aimed at defusing
tension between Iran and the Taliban. But Umar said that he wants
reply to the points he has raised.
</P>
<P>
If these points are not taken into consideration, they would be
left with no other option but to render sacrifice and fight for
their rights, he added. 
</P>
