<HEADLINE> Hunan Fights Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Over six million people in
central China's Hunan Province are now fighting a severe drought
which hit the province's central and southern areas in June.
</P>
<P>
While record floods devastated parts of Hunan Province in July
and August, drought was plaguing six of its prefectures and cities,
affecting some 0.7 million hectares of farm land, and affecting the
drinking-water supply of 1.25 million people.
</P>
<P>
"We call on people to combat the drought with the same spirit
demonstrated in the anti-flood campaign a month ago," a provincial
official said.
</P>
<P>
At present, tens of thousands of government officials of
severely affected Chenzhou and Shaoyang have been mobilized to the
anti-drought front line.
</P>
<P>
Solving the drinking-water problem has been given priority, and
local people are busy drilling wells and water channels.
</P>
<P>
Provincial calls for concerted efforts since the drought began
are expected to continue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
