<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Report Says Population Under Control (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China's efforts to control
population growth have proven successful, with a population that
is 200 million less than what it could have been had nothing been
done, according to the State Statistical Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
A SSB report says that population changes have helped improve
the national strength and people's living standard and provide a
favorable environment for the opening and reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
In the 30 years between the founding of China and the late
1980s, China's birth rate remained at above 30 per thousand and it
was not until the 1980s that it fell to around 20 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
The large population and high growth rate had been a heavy
burden and have seriously hampered economic and social development
and had a negative effect on people's lives.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, the fast economic and social development has
helped change people's ideas about children, and the population
growth rate has fallen sharply.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, China had 1.236 billion people, with a
birth rate of 16.57 per thousand and a natural growth rate of
10.06 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
The family planning has, to some degree, eased the pressure on
clothing, food, housing, transportation, education, medicine,
resources, environment, and in other areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
