<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Suspends Bank Branch Applications Processing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines is suspending for three months the processing of bank
branch applications following a review of the existing bank
branching policies and guidelines, Central Bank Governor Gabriel
Singson said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the measure took effect Thursday following the
approval of the Monetary Board Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank, Singson said, is currently reviewing the bank
branching policies and guidelines for rural banks, thrift banks
and commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the review is to avoid over-branching and help
encourage mergers, consolidations and buy-ins especially for banks
with many branches, he said.
</P>
<P>
The review is also aimed at curbing the practice of some small
banks in opening up several branches and then folding up later on,
Singson said.
</P>
<P>
Since the liberalization of bank branching several years ago,
there has been an "explosion" of new branches in the Philippines.
Four small banks have already shut down in the country since the
outbreak of the currency crisis last year.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has been encouraging banks to merger in order
to survive the prolonged financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Towns to Be Constructed for Flood Victims (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
State Development Planning Commission official Liu Fuyuan
said the Chinese economy is facing a surplus of rural laborers and
overproduction in the cities. To solve the problems, the most
efficient method is to speed up township construction and upgrade
living standards for the 900 million Chinese rural residents.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale township construction in the flooded areas was
undertaken in some part of east China's Anhui Province in 1991,
when floods destroyed three million houses.
</P>
<P>
For the post-flood reconstruction, the Anhui provincial
government reorganized the scattered population into small towns,
and within three months, 500,000 flood victims were
resettled. This reconstruction project was cited for an award by
the United Nations in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The restruction plan estimates that at least 50-
million-square-meters of housing will be built, bringing a
market demand of 25 billion yuan (about 3 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Zhou Shulian, a research fellow at the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences, said that upgrading rural areas will expand domestic
demand, especially in the rural market.
</P>
<P>
So far, reconstruction plans for Hubei, Heilongjiang and other
flood-stricken provinces have already been drafted. Some places,
such as the city of Daqing in Heilongjiang Province, have already
begun reconstruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
