<HEADLINE> Nepal to Stress Development Aid at UN General Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Nepal will stress the
issues of overseas development aid and south-south cooperation at
the ongoing 53rd session of the U.N. General Assembly, a Foreign
Ministry official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Acting Foreign Secretary Shyam Anand Suman told a press
conference that Nepal will focus on the overseas development aid
provided by the developed countries to the least developed and
land-locked countries like Nepal.
</P>
<P>
He said the developed countries should contribute 0.07 percent
of their gross domestic product (GDP) as aid to the least
developed countries and 0.15 percent of their GDP to the
land-locked countries.
</P>
<P>
Nepal will also stress south-south cooperation at the U.N.
General Assembly, he said, adding that during the 12th Summit of
the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) early this month in South Africa,
Vietnam, Brazil and Malaysia had proposed specific programs in
this regard.
</P>
<P>
At the NAM summit, Nepal also focused on overseas development
aid and south-south cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We will also raise the issues of debt relief, peace,
development and disarmament including small arms disarmament,"
Suman said.
</P>
<P>
Environment protection and human rights will also be Nepal's
concerns at the U.N. General Assembly, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said his country supports the proposal of limited expansion
of permanent and non-permanent membership of the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
And Nepal lays emphasis on U.N. reform and restructuring which
includes the reduction of its budget and staff, but it should not
affect the land-locked countries and the least developed
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Water Resources Shailaja
Acharya is scheduled to attend the U.N. General Assembly on behalf
of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
But she has canceled an agreed ensuing official visit to Canada
and four members of parliament have been dropped from the
delegation because of domestic political developments, Suman told
the press. He did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) and other minor opposition parties
Wednesday registered a motion at the Parliament Secretariat
against Speaker of Lower House Ram Chandra Poudel.
</P>
<P>
They alleged that the role played by the speaker in passing the
Local Autonomy Bill last week in the house was against the
parliamentary democratic system.
</P>
<P>
When the opposition MPs were voicing their protest against the
bill, Speaker Poudel, who is from the ruling Nepali Congress,
conducted voice voting on the bill and declared that it had been
passed by the house.
</P>
<P>
It takes one week for the motion to be mature before the house
can discuss it, and a two-third majority is needed in the house to
force its speaker out of power.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Nepali Congress and its ruling partner the
Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) registered a
similar motion against Deputy Speaker Lila Shrestha Subba who is
from the CPN-UML. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
