<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Reiterates Cross-Straits Political Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Tang Shubei, executive vice
president of the Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Strait (ARATS), today reiterated China's stance on a mainland
visit by Lee Teng-hui, the current leader of Taiwan authorities.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, President Jiang Zemin said that leaders of
Taiwan authorities were welcome to visit the mainland in a proper
capacity and noted the possibility of a reciprocal visit to
Taiwan, according to the ARATS leader. Tang made the comments in
response to a question concerning Lee's pledge to undertake a
so-called "journey of peace" to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that a Lee visit to the mainland is of course a
matter of politics, and stressed that any such visit should be
preceded by political talks between ARATS and the Straits Exchange
Foundation (SEF).
</P>
<P>
Tang noted that ARATS-SEF meetings over the years have fully
demonstrated the difficulty in negotiating practical issues in the
absence of political talks. He stressed that negotiations on
practical issues often involve judicial jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
Political disparity constitutes the key issue in the
cross-Straits question, said Tang, adding that the reasonable way to
settle the question in accordance with the development of the
cross-Straits relations to hold political talks between the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that ARATS and SEF will be able to find
common ground for political talks through mutual exchanges,
and noted that all topics which will be helpful for achieving
peaceful reunification and the development of cross-Straits
relations are open to discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
