<HEADLINE> Iran to Keep Troops at Afghan Border: Iranian Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Iran will keep its troops
at its eastern border with Afghanistan, "as long as it feels
insecure," Iranian Ambassador to Pakistan Mehdi Akhundazdeh said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at a press conference, "Our troops would
remain there to safeguard our national integrity against growing
cross-border drug trafficking, but their posture will remain
defensive."
</P>
<P>
He said some 400 Iranian security troops, including a senior
commander, have been killed in clashes with drug traffickers at
the Iran-Afghan border over the past year.
</P>
<P>
Iran's heavy troop deployment at its eastern border was aimed
at deterring drug trafficking activities, the envoy said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Iran's military exercises along its border with
Afghanistan, Akhundazdeh said these maneuvers were an annual
feature to mark anniversary of Iraq's invasion against Iran after
the success of the Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the state of Pak-Iran relations in the
backdrop of recent developments in Afghanistan, he said he felt
saddened that events in Afghanistan and consequent developments
had a spill over on the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed the hope that "with the sincere and
genuine efforts by the leaders of both sides this spill over can
be contained."
</P>
<P>
He also referred to the recent meeting of Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif and Iranian President Sayed Muhammad Khatami
in New York and called for follow-up efforts in this respect.
</P>
<P>
Akhundzadeh urged Pakistan, which recognized Taliban, to
influence the Taliban administration to return the bodies of
remaining slain Iranian diplomats and release more than 40 Iranian
drivers taken prisoner by its forces.
</P>
<P>
He called for a dialogue between the warring factions in
Afghanistan to settle the lingering crisis. "Uzbeks, Tajiks,
Hazaras and Pushtuns (in Afghanistan) should sit together and
settle their differences," he added.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about U.S. policy towards Afghanistan,
the Iranian diplomat said, "As far as Iran is concerned, it was
meant to create problems for us."
</P>
<P>
He did not rule out the possibility of conflicting economic
interests of different countries in the region which led to
instability in Afghanistan. "It is always outside interference in
our region which causes disturbance," he said without elaborating.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
