<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Law Week In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese will get a chance to
see how Westerners deal with a criminal case at a trial staged as
part of British Law Week from October 6 to 10, whose purpose is to
increase comprehensive legal exchanges between Britain and China,
according to Stephen Forbes, second secretary of the British
Embassy in China.
</P>
<P>
Forbes told a press conference here today that the case being
brought to trial will be a robbery and that it will be presided
over by Lord Justice Otton, with two leading British QCs as the
defence and prosecution counsel. The jury will be made up of
senior Chinese members of the legal professional.
</P>
<P>
He said that it will be broadcast by Chinese television and a
that panel discussion will follow the trial.
</P>
<P>
British Law Weeks have been held in France and Spain, but this
one is the first foreign law week to be held in China.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 Chinese and British lawyers, judges, legislators
and academics will come together for four days of discussions. The
group is led by the Court Appeal Judge the Rt. Hon. Lord Justice
Otton and includes senior barristers, solicitors, academics, human
rights experts, representatives of British NGOs and other
practitioners of the law.
</P>
<P>
The Week features discussions on issues of current interest to
the legal professions of both countries, focusing on criminal
procedure, law and policing, and the prosecution services.
</P>
<P>
The Week is the result of a partnership between the Chinese
Ministry of Justice, the Cultural and Education Sector of the
British Embassy, and the Great Britain-China Center of London,
according to Wang Lixian, director of the Foreign Affairs
Department of the Chinese Ministry of Justice.
</P>
<P>
Forbes said that both countries hope to understand each other
better, because if a country's legal system is clear and
understandable to foreigners, investment will come easier.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
