<HEADLINE> Myanmar Allows Some NLD Members to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar authorities have
allowed seven members of the National League for Democracy (NLD)
to return home in the last two days after "housing" them for
several weeks at the state guest houses, according to a government
statement issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The authorities had also allowed an 85-year-old senior member
of the party to return home on September 14.
</P>
<P>
The official information sheet said more NLD members, who are
still "housed" at the guest houses, will be permitted to return
home in coming weeks after "discussions" between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement issued here Thursday by the NLD, a
total of 921 NLD members including 200 parliament
representatives-elect and 721 organizers have been detained by the
authorities since May 27 this year.
</P>
<P>
The NLD denied that the authorities had discussions with its
detained members, saying that they were, in fact, "interrogated."
</P>
<P>
Concerning the detention of some NLD members recently, the
government said it has no wish to "house" them for any longer than
necessary, and they will soon be home if the NLD leaders
cooperate.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday last week, the NLD unilaterally formed a 10-member
Committee Representing the People's Parliament Elected in the
1990 General Election to arrange for the convening of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
A People's Parliament was also formed on the same day with a
chairman elected.
</P>
<P>
The government has rejected the formation, saying it will
continue to govern the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
