<HEADLINE> ASEAN to Nominate Malaysia for UN Security Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 24 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN foreign ministers
have unanimously agreed to nominate Malaysia as a non-permanent
member of the United Nations Security Council, Malaysia's national
news agency Bernama reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers at their annual gathering in New York also agreed
to nominate Thailand for the post of director-general of the World
Trade Organization (WTO) and Indonesia as a member of the
Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC), the news agency quoted
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi as saying in New
York.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN foreign ministers decided that it was too early to
set a date for Cambodia's admission into the regional grouping as
the business of setting up a government in Phnom Penh following
the elections had yet to be finalized.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN foreign ministers also discussed preparations for the
sixth ASEAN summit scheduled to be held in Hanoi on December 15
and 16.
</P>
<P>
The summit would receive three documents relating to the
economic and financial crisis affecting the ASEAN region, the
implementation of development programs to realize the ASEAN Vision
2020 and the joint ASEAN Foreign and Economic Ministers Report,
Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
