<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Reading Habits Tend To Be Diverse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Some changes in Chinese
reading habits since 1978 show greater diversification, according
to a study by the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS).
</P>
<P>
The study, done by CAS's National Conditions Research Group, is
the first of the kind since the founding of new China in 1949. It
involved officials, people in bookstores, and ordinary folk and
found that books before 1978 were thought to be monotonous and
concentrated mainly on the works of Chairman Mao, revolutionary
literature encouraged by the government, and the Chinese classics.
</P>
<P>
The government and Chinese cultural traditions played a major
role in readers' lives at that time.
</P>
<P>
The shortage of books was a common story in the past, but what
people worry about now is how to choose from so many books on the
shelves, says Dr. Kang Xiaoguang, a member of the National
Conditions Research Group who is in charge of the study.
</P>
<P>
With the growth in the number of books came diversification and
an improvement in quality since 1978. The study found that the
influence of the Chinese classics has declined since 1978 and that
the impact of foreign literature, which was popular at the
beginning of China's reforms started to decline in the early
1990s. The revolutionary literature represented by Lu Xun, which
had a dominant role in readers' lives 20 years ago, has gradually
been replaced by non-revolutionary literature.
</P>
<P>
It should be noted, however, that the influence of Deng
Xiaoping's selected works has gone up steadily since 1978. During
the late 1980s, the influence of how-to books and economics began
to increase rapidly. Books on religion, biographies, and books
like "China Can Say No" and "Looking At China With the Third Eye"
have had a special impact on readers.
</P>
<P>
Researchers say that to many readers, what they read is no
longer a "political problem". "Over the past 20 years, reading has
become a personal matter in China," Kang says.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe that Chinese readers and publishers have
gradually matured over the past 20 years and that the market
economy gives readers more choices.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
