<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Start Post-Flood Rehabilitation Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina said here Thursday that the post-flood
rehabilitation work would start in the country next month.
</P>
<P>
Some 170 million taka (3.62 million U.S. dollars) has been
earmarked for housing, 215.6 million taka (4.59 million dollars)
for agricultural rehabilitation, and 640 million taka (13.62
million dollars) for sinking tubewells across the country, Hasina
told reporters at the International Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
New agricultural loans would be given to the affected farmers
before realizing the previous ones, to help them recoup the losses
caused by the floods, the prime minister said while exchanging
views with and seeking suggestions from journalists on measures to
tackle problems faced by the government following the floods.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question, she said the buying capacity of the
people in the rural areas has been reduced, "but when the
food-for-work and the rehabilitation activities start, people
would get back their purchasing capacity."
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the deaths caused by diarrhea, Hasina said some
322,000 people have been affected by the disease and 336 of them
have died, adding that the government is aware of the situation
and has taken measures to cope with it.
</P>
<P>
The government has instructed the construction of government
buildings at the thana (township) level on raised lands which
could be used as relief centers during calamities, and there would
be a pond in every ward for storing drinking water, she said.
</P>
<P>
Hasina ruled out the possibility of price hike of food grains
in the country after the floods. "Under the prevailing situation,
there is no possibility of price hike of food grains in the
country," she said.
</P>
<P>
The price of rice went up a little following rumors about the
food stock, but it was handled properly by the government,
according to the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
The government has now a food stock of 647,000 tons, and the
private sector has imported 1.5 million tons to meet the
requirements of food, she said.
</P>
<P>
She warned that stern measures would be taken against those
found misusing the relief materials.
</P>
<P>
The protracted floods which started hitting the country in
early July affected directly and indirectly about half of the
country's 127 million people, with nearly 30 million of them hit
seriously, leaving more than 1,000 people dead and inflicting a
preliminary estimated loss of about 3.4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
