<HEADLINE> Hopes of Rate Cut Bring Buyers Back to Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Expectations of a cut in
U.S. interest rates brought buyers back into the sharemarket
Thursday, powering it more than 1.5 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 41.3 points higher at 2,614.9,
but off its high of 2,634.4 after a wave of profit-taking earlier
the day.
</P>
<P>
The buying scramble extended to markets worldwide, with Japan
and Hong Kong also closing sharply higher.
</P>
<P>
The bourses rose following comments by U.S. Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan overnight, which were seen as indicating
the U.S. was set to cut interest rates to combat the threat of
recession posed by Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index finished 76 points higher at 4,593.1,
with much of the buying interest in blue-chip stocks including
leading banks.
</P>
<P>
Westpac continued its strong run with a 33 cent improvement,
while NAB was up 67 cents as strong yielding banking shares were
favored in a potential lower interest rate environment.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth improved 19 cents and ANZ added 16 cents.
</P>
<P>
Insurance major AMP was up 13 cents, while its takeover target
GIO went against trend to drop six cents.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, global media group News Corp maintained its
improvement, in line with the rise in the company's ADRs in the
U.S. The ordinary shares improved 38 cents, while the preferreds
rose 31 cents.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications major Telstra rose six cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index had a 12.7 point improvement to
1,019.4, with good rises in mid-size companies such as zinc
company Pasminco, which was up five cents.
</P>
<P>
BHP performed in line with most resources, rising 17.1 cents
while WMC was up seven and Rio Tinto had a 26.9 cents improvement.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was up 17.4 points to 1,056.5 as the bullion
price increased 3.85 per ounce to 291.20 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was 372.31 million shares traded at a value of 1.204
billion Australian dollars (698.32 million U.S. dollars), a marked
increase in activity over recent days. There were 711 rises and
493 falls, with 367 steady. 
</P>
