<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Gets ADB Loan for Urban Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) approved Thursday a 70-million-U.S.-dollar loan for Sri
Lanka to improve urban infrastructure and to finance housing
improvements for low-income households.
</P>
<P>
The Urban Development and Low-Income Housing Project will
support government efforts to give local authorities more
responsibility for providing and financing infrastructure and
municipal services, the Manila-based bank said.
</P>
<P>
The project will improve roads, water supply and drainage
systems, bus terminals and public markets in up to 27 towns in Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
"The project is expected to have a significant impact on the
capacities and performance of local authorities in managing urban
infrastructure and in increasing the availability of affordable
market-rate financing to low-income households," says William
Costin, an ADB senior specialist.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the project is 100 million dollars. The ADB
loan will come from its Special Funds resources, which are
interest-free and repayable over 40 years. 
</P>
