<HEADLINE> U.S. Grain Company Build Factory In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. company of Cargill
has recently established a factory with an annual capacity of
250,000 tons of fodder in Zhenjiang, east China's Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
Cargill, which has moved its headquarters from Hong Kong to
Shanghai, mainly processes and sells agricultural products and
food and is involved in financial businesses. Last year the
company had global sales of 51 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dan Huber, president of Cargill Asia-Pacific, says that the
company has been doing business in China since 1972, after
President Nixon's visit. It sells grain, oil-bearing seeds, cotton
and fertilizer to China and buys iron and corn. From 1996 to 1997,
its trade with China amounted to one billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Huber says that, because of the impact of the Asian financial
crisis, food sales in the latter half of 1997 dropped 15 to 20
percent and the fodder business also suffered losses.
</P>
<P>
However, he expressed optimism about the Chinese market, and
explained that better products and promoting the development of
China's agriculture are two goals of the company. 
</P>
