<HEADLINE> Media Impartiality, Focus of Attention in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Media impartiality has been
the focal point of attention of Australia's media groups Thursday
as Australia's election campaign entered its final 9 days.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the competing major political parties, including
Prime Minister John Howard, Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer and
Opposition leader Kim Beazley, faced questions from journalists
about the favorable comments by media barons about the prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Kerry Packer, owner of the nation's largest commercial
television network Nine Network and dozens of magazines, and Don
McDonald, chairman of the state-funded Australian Broadcasting
Corporation (ABC), praised the prime minister Wednesday at a
fund-raising lunch attended by the prime minister and some
business barons.
</P>
<P>
Kim Beazley, leader of the Australian Labor Party, Thursday
dismissed the media magnate's endorsement of Howard as
insignificant, while Treasurer Peter Costello said the remarks
were unlikely to translate into favorable media coverage.
</P>
<P>
Packer said Howard deserved re-election as prime minister and
attacked the opposition party, saying the Australian Labor Party
needed to be in opposition for a few more years.
</P>
<P>
Packer, who was given free digital spectrum for his network by
the government this year, needs the support of the federal
government to change some regulations that prevent him from
acquiring the nation's two leading newspapers The Sydney Morning
Herald and The Age while controlling the Nine Network.
</P>
<P>
McDonald, a Howard government appointee, said at the beginning
of the lunch that Howard was a man of high courage, decency and
true humility.
</P>
<P>
His glowing comment sparked a protest Thursday by some ABC
employees.
</P>
<P>
Community and Public Sector Union (CPSU) staff at the ABC
headquarters in Sydney walked off the job for three hours in
protest against McDonald's public endorsement of Prime Minister
John Howard.
</P>
<P>
The ABC chairman's comment came as a surprise as the prime
minister a week ago accused the ABC of bias against his coalition.
</P>
<P>
Recent media coverage by the nation's leading national
newspapers, including The Australian owned by Rupert Murdoch, has
been critical of the Labor Party's policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
