<HEADLINE> Industrial Unrest Imminent in Nigeria over Wage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- An industrial unrest seems
imminent in Lagos and Osun states following the insistence of the
states' civil servants on the 5,200 Naira (about 60 U.S. Dollars)
minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
The Council of Industrial Union (COIU) issued a seven-day
ultimatum to Lagos state government to implement the new minimum
wage in a statement released at the end of an emergency meeting
Wednesday, The Post Express reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
COIU Chairman Ayodele Akele warned that the state civil
servants would not accept anything less than the 5,200 Naira wage
taking effect from September 1 or the state government would face
an industrial unrest.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Lagos State Administrator Mohammed Marwa said the
state requires about 10.2 billion Naira (about 113 million U.S.
Dollars) yearly to implement the new minimum wages, saying the
state may find it difficult to shoulder the extra burden.
</P>
<P>
The COIU leaders said they regretted the remarks made by the
administrator and issued the seven-day ultimatum with effect from
Thursday or September 24.
</P>
<P>
Their counterparts in Osun State are also insisting on the
5,200 Naira minimum wage against the 2,800 (32.3 U.S. Dollars)
Naira which the state government is proposing to pay.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the Nigerian Federal Government approved a
pay rise package for civil servants with the monthly minimum wage
at 5,200 Naira.
</P>
<P>
However, the government said in a circular to all ministries
and government bodies that the pay rise was only for civil
servants working for the Federal government, while workers of
State governments have to negotiate with their respective
employers for necessary adjustment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
