<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Membership Linked With Democracy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's suspension from the
Commonwealth will not be lifted until a democratic civilian
government is in place next year, Secretary-General of the
Commonwealth Chief Emeka Anyaoku has said.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku made the comments in London Wednesday, shortly after a
meeting with visiting Nigerian military leader General Abdulsalam
Abubakar, who is on his way to the U.N. General Assembly in New
York.
</P>
<P>
He described the meeting as excellent and very productive,
adding that Nigeria and the Commonwealth are working toward
normalizing relations between them.
</P>
<P>
He said the Commonwealth had already begun talks with the
Independent Electoral Commission (INEC) on assistance to the
latter for the organization of elections under Nigeria's
transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
According to the new transition program announced by Abubakar,
Nigeria's military will hand over power to an elected civilian
government on May 29, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku said there were moves not only in the Commonwealth,
but also across Europe, to lift sanctions imposed on Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
In his own remarks after the meeting, Abubakar expressed the
hope that the Commonwealth will eventually re-admit Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He said the Commonwealth was already playing a significant
role in the transition program and was looking into ways of
participating in the development of Nigeria's economy.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar attended a reception for British businessmen later
Wednesday before leaving for New York.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's membership was suspended from the Commonwealth in
1995 after the then government of late General Sani Abacha
executed author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other minority activists
on murder charges.
</P>
<P>
International sanctions, including the ban of top military
government officials from overseas visits, were also imposed on
Nigeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
