<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Malaysians Charged for Spreading Rumors on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Four Malaysians,
including a woman, were charged Thursday in four magistrate's
courts here and in Petaling Jaya near here for circulating rumors
on the Internet about alleged riots in the city in early August,
Malaysia's national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
This is the first case of its kind in Malaysia. The charged are
Au Yong Way, 27, a bank officer; Lee Chun Meng, 40, a
construction site supervisor; Wong Yoon Sing, 37, a finance
manager; and Tan Lai Yee, 25, a computer firm logistics trainee.
</P>
<P>
They pleaded not guilty under section 505 (b) of the Penal Code
which carries a maximum two years' jail or fine, or both, on
conviction.
</P>
<P>
Au, who is alleged to have committed the offense on August 3
this year, was allowed bail of 2,000 ringgit (526 U.S. dollars) in
one surety pending trial on November 11.
</P>
<P>
Lee, charged with committing the offense on July 30, was
allowed the same amount of bail pending trial on May 20 next year.
</P>
<P>
Wong who was said to commit the offense on August 8 was allowed
bail of 6,000 ringgit (1,578 U.S. dollars) in one surety pending
trial on October 22.
</P>
<P>
And Tan charged with committing the offense at her workplace on
August 3 was allowed bail of 5,000 ringgit (1,315 U.S. dollars) in
one surety pending trial on December 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
