<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Be Accepted as Nuclear Weapons State: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- An Indian senior official
said Thursday that the core issue for India to accept any formal
measure to restrain its nuclear capabilities was its acceptance as
a nuclear weapons state by the nuclear weapons powers.
</P>
<P>
Giving a lecture on "India, Europe and Non-Proliferation" at
Jawahrlal Nehru University here, Jasjit Singh, director of the
Institute for Defense Studies and Analyses (IDSA), said that as
India was unlikely to join the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty
(CTBT) or any fissile material cut-off treaty, a protocol to the
Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) can be attached where
countries like India will commit to the obligations of the NPT but
as a state for nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
After India conducted five underground nuclear tests in May
this year, the world community has time and again urged India to
stop nuclear weapons development program and sign CTBT without any
condition.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee Wednesday said that
India would sign CTBT only its conditions are met. India is
reported to have asked four conditions for the signing of CTBT:
recognizing India's nuclear status, lifting economic sanctions,
keeping its minimum nuclear deterrence and transfer of advanced
dual use of technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
