The Nigerian Defense Headquarters alleged that five Nigerian
soldiers, 20 women and 18 children had been injured in the
clashes in April and about 15 fishermen were taken hostage by
Camerounian troops.
</P>
<P>
According to former Defense spokesman Colonel Godwin Ugbo,
despite Camerounian President Paul Biya's denial that his army
had attacked Nigerian army position in the disputed areas,
Camerounian gendarmes have opened new fronts at some border towns
in Borno State, the local newspapers said. 
