<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Build Global Monitoring Circle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- China is pushing ahead with
plans to build the world's first global ground-based meridian
circle to forecast conditions for satellite launches, manned space
shuttles and airplane and ship navigation.
</P>
<P>
Wei Fengsi, a researcher at the Space Science and Application
Center attached to the Chinese Academy of Sciences, said today
that "the meridian circle will monitor sun storms, geomagnetic
storms and electromagnetic radiation."
</P>
<P>
He said the building of the network is aimed at avoiding
satellite launch failures, satellite malfunctions and inaccurate
plane navigation.
</P>
<P>
As part of a future space development strategy, China will be
the first to build a chain of ground stations along a span of 120
degrees east longitude which will later form a global meridian
circle with monitoring stations along 60 degrees west longitude
built by the U.S. and Canada, Wei said.
</P>
<P>
China has so far built some 20 well-equipped ground monitoring
stations and seven related labs along the 120 degrees east
longitude, according to Wei.
</P>
<P>
In 2003, China plans to send the world most advanced solar
telescope into space orbit. The telescope is being jointly
developed by China and Germany with an investment of 500 million
yuan (60.2 million U.S. dollars) to forecast and monitor solar
activity.
</P>
<P>
Shao Liqin, a senior official with the Ministry of Science and
Technology, said the central government has approved the
"meridian chain project" and has promised to pump 180 million yuan
(about 21.7 million U.S. dollars) into it. The project is expected
to be completed within five years.
</P>
<P>
Scientists from the United States, Canada, Japan, Russia,
Australia, France and other countries have expressed their
willingness to cooperate with China in this endeavor.
</P>
<P>
The State Natural Science Fund will offer 5 million yuan (about
602,000 U.S. dollars) to support research on the relationship
between space conditions and their consequences on earth.
</P>
<P>
"China is the only place in the world where a meridian circle
linking to the western hemisphere can be formed for effective
monitoring of space conditions, because most of the areas covered
by other longitude circles are oceans," Wei said.
</P>
<P>
"After receiving forecast of dangerous conditions, preventive
measures can be taken, such as orbit readjustments for satellites,
the postponement of space walks for astronauts, and alterations of
telecommunications channels in order to minimize losses," said Wei.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xiji, an expert on aerospace, said 40 percent of China's
satellite failures are caused by catastrophic space conditions,
including wind shear at high altitudes. Economic losses can be
greatly reduced and accident rates can be lowered if more data
about space conditions are collected beforehand, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ESCAP Unveils Reform to Meet Millennium Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Economic
and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) has
announced a revised secretariat structure to meet the demands of
the 21st century, a press release from the U.N. body said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring which streamlines ESCAP's programs structure
is the final phase of the reform process that began in January
1996, to comply with the overall U.N. reforms effort and the
provisions of a Commission resolution, ESCAP Secretary-General
Adrianus Mooy was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Most of the revised secretariat structure came into immediate
effect, while some have been slated for January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
"The secretariat restructuring aims to conform to the crux of
the reform exercise... and enable ESCAP to respond more
effectively to the evolving economic and social needs of members
and associate members through multi-disciplinary and intersectoral
action," Mooy said.
</P>
<P>
The reorganization has been welcomed by many member states, the
press release said.
</P>
<P>
The reform of the regional commissions like ESCAP offer the
possibility of greatly improving the overall efficiency of the
U.N., it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
