<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Appoints Deputy Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin on Thursday appointed Valentina Matvienko, former
ambassador to Greece, as deputy prime minister in charge of social
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Matvienko, 49, was a deputy of the Soviet parliament from 1989
to 1991, heading its committee on family and children's issues,
and a member of the parliament's presidium, where she worked with
Yevgeny Primakov, now Russia's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
In the 1970s and 1980s, Matvienko was an active member of the
Communist Party Youth League.
</P>
<P>
Matvienko will have to address some serious social problems,
such as high unemployment rate and huge arrears of wages and
pensions, the Moscow Times said. 
</P>
