<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Spokesman on Blair's China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The forthcoming China visit
by British Prime Minister Tony Blair would help push Sino-British
friendly cooperation to a higher level, said Chinese Foreign
Ministry Spokesman Zhu Bangzao.
</P>
<P>
Blair will pay an official visit to China from October 6 to 10
at the invitation of Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, the spokesman
announced at a regular press conference here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Blair would exchange ideas on Sino-British
relations and the international issues of common concern with
Chinese leaders, the spokesman said, adding that the British Prime
Minister would also visit Shanghai, the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region as well as Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Blair's China tour "will be another major event in Sino-British
relations" after the smooth transfer of power in Hong Kong last
year, he noted.
</P>
<P>
China and Britain, both influential nations in the world and
permanent members of the UN Security Council, enjoy extensive
common interests and shoulder important responsibility in the
areas of safeguarding world peace and promoting common economic
development, Zhu stated.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that under the current international situation
that is undergoing profound changes, the further growth of
Sino-British ties not only conforms to the fundamental interests
of the two countries, but also serves the world peace, stability
and prosperity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
