<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise Sharply in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose sharply in
Tokyo Thursday as investors bought back shares on euphoria which
spilled into the Tokyo market from overseas stock markets over a
possible cut in U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange jumped 415.97 points, or 3.02
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 14,205.78. The Tokyo
market was closed Wednesday for a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, rose 27.84 points or 2.65 percent to
1,078.01.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the major section fell to an estimated 450 million
shares from Tuesday's 511.83 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Steel maker NKK was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders hailed fresh hints left by Federal Reserve Board
Chairman Alan Greenspan of lower U.S. interest rates and some
predict it could happen as early as next week during a meeting of
the Federal Open Markets Committee, the policy arm of the
U.S. Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts see this as a plus because it means the United
States is serious about preventing the world financial crisis from
spreading.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,342 issues listed on the First Section, gainers
exceeded losers 871 to 290, with 133 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0930 GMT, September 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia -- Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen
said here Thursday that the attacker who fired rockets on his
motorcade would not be punished if he voluntarily surrendered
himself and confessed the wire-puller.
</P>
<P>
Two rocket-propelled grenades were launched at the car of Hun
Sen who was on his way to the King Norodom Sihanouk's palace to
attend the new National Assembly session Thursday morning. Hun Sen
escaped uninjured, but a child was killed on the spot. Three
others were seriously wounded and one of them died in the hospital
later. (Cambodia-Attack-Hun Sen)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Russia will offer 180 million U.S. dollars next year to
help Ukraine build two nuclear power stations, Ukraine President
Leonid Kuchma has announced here.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma told local reporters that during his talks with Russian
leaders in Moscow on September 18 and 19, Russia agreed to set
aside 180 million dollars from its next year's budget to fund the
building of the Rovno station and the Khmelynitsky station. He
stressed that Ukraine would go ahead with the projects with the
cooperation from Russia, no matter whether the European Bank of
Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) would extend its promised
fund of 750 million dollars to the stations.
(Ukraine-Russia-Nuclear Power)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SIEM REAP -- The 122 new lawmakers, along with diplomats and
some dignitaries, attended the opening ceremony of the new
National Assembly in Siem Reap Thursday at the residence of King
Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
Second Prime Minister and Vice-President of Cambodian People's
Party (CPP) Hun Sen, Prince Ranariddh of the Funcinpec party, and
Sam Rainsy of the Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) all attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia held a National Assembly election on July
26. Thirty-nine political parties, 19 more than in the
UN-administered election in 1993, were vying for 122 parliamentary
seats and the right to form a new government. The previous
National Assembly of 120 members was elected five years ago and
its tenure expired on Thursday. (Cambodia-National Assembly)
</P>
<P>
