</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. House and Senate negotiators on Wednesday
approved a 250.5-billion-U.S.-dollar defense spending plan, which
is smaller than what President Bill Clinton and some Republican
lawmakers had called for.
</P>
<P>
The spending approved by the lawmakers is 2.8 billion dollars
above the current levels but 485 million dollars below a White
House request. The approval was made after a closed session to
work out differences between House and Senate defense spending
plans for the new fiscal year that starts October 1. (US-Military
Spending) 
</P>
