<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life Expectancy Exceeds 70 in South China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The average life expectancy
in Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province, now
exceeds 70, according to a survey released here today.
</P>
<P>
The survey said that citizens at or above 65 years old, now
account for 10.97 percent of the city's total population, compared
with 8.49 percent in 1990, and Guangzhou's birth rate is dropping year
by year.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that the average family now consists of
3.45 people, a drop of 25 percent since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Families are also spending 19.5 percent more on education, and
there are now more than 1,700 people with university degrees per
10,000 people, or 17.72 percent of the local population. The
illiteracy rate in the city has also dropped to 4.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, per capita living space has reached 13.02 square
meters. There is now one color TV and an air conditioner for each
family, and 95 washing machines and refrigerators per 100
households. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
