<HEADLINE> Cambodia Rocket Attack Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, Cambodia, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian Second
Prime Minister Hun Sen said here Thursday that the attacker who
fired rockets on his motorcade would not be punished if he
voluntarily surrendered himself and confessed the wire-puller.
</P>
<P>
Two rocket-propelled grenades were launched at the car of Hun
Sen who was on his way to the King Norodom Sihanouk's palace to
attend the new National Assembly session Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen escaped uninjured, but a child was killed on the
spot. Three others were seriously wounded and one of them died in
the hospital later.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen told a press conference that the government has offered
200,000 U.S. dollars for information about the backstage
manipulator of the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian government also strongly condemned the attack
Thursday and called for a comprehensive investigation into the
case.
</P>
<P>
The 122 new lawmakers, along with diplomats and some
dignitaries, attended the opening ceremony of the new National
Assembly in Siem Reap Thursday at Sihanouk's residence.
</P>
<P>
Second Prime Minister and Vice-President of the Cambodian
People's Party (CPP) Hun Sen, Prince Ranariddh of the Funcinpec
party, and Sam Rainsy of the Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) all attended
the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia held a National Assembly election on July 26. The
ruling CPP won 64 seats in the election, followed by Funcinpec
Party with 43 seats and the SRP with 15 seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
