<HEADLINE> Ugandan MPs Back Army Presence in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's members of
Parliament Wednesday expressed overwhelming support for the
continued deployment of Uganda People's Defense Forces (UPDF) in
eastern part of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
They made the decision when debating on President Yoweri
Museveni's speech addressed to the legislature last week.
</P>
<P>
The MPs also supported the president's diplomatic efforts for
a negotiated settlement to the deepening crisis in the war-torn
country, the New Vision daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The debate was reportedly adjourned prematurely after an MP
alleged that more than 1,000 UPDF troops had been taken prisoner
in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
This allegation was immediately rebutted by Major General
Mugisha Muntu and Minister of State for Defense Steven Kavuma.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has been accused of fomenting and backing the Tutsi-led
rebellion in Congo since its eruption on August 2. It admitted
military presence in eastern Congo, but said it is to safeguard
Uganda's national security.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan government said it has never been directly
involved in the conflict between Congolese rebels and government
troops loyal to President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
When addressing parliament on the situation in Congo (K) last
week, President Museveni said UPDF troops will remain there till
their national interests are not threatened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
