<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Analyst Says Silting Not Main Reason For Summer's Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A veteran water conservation
specialist believes that this summer's serious flood problems on
the Yangtze River were caused more by the reduced amount of water
diversion areas than by silting.
</P>
<P>
Water levels on many sections of the middle and lower reaches
of the Yangtze were much higher than 44 years ago and many
specialists think that this was the result of silting.
</P>
<P>
But, Hong Qingyu, formerly Chief Engineer of the Yangtze River
Water Conservation Committee, sees it differently.
</P>
<P>
According to him, amounts of floodwater this summer were less
than that in 1954, and only parts of the main course of the
Yangtze were more silted, while most sections were normal.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, the high water levels were mainly the result of
a decrease in the amount of diverted water. In 1954, a total of
102.3 billion cubic meters of water were diverted from the lower
and middle reaches, compared with only 10 billion cubic meters
this summer, he explains. Because there was more water in the
river, the water levels were higher.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the high water levels is that more water was
being drained into the river to prevent waterlogging than in
1954. This was the result of improved drainage ability, Hong
points out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
