<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prices of Precious Metals Soar on U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Prices of silver and
other precious metals rose sharply Wednesday on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, following U.S. Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan's
hints of lowering interest rate.
</P>
<P>
Silver for December delivery rose 15.3 cents, or 3.1 percent,
to 5.043 U.S. dollars an ounce; December gold rose 2 dollars to
292.50 dollars an ounce. October platinum rose 2.20 dollars to
355.50 dollars an ounce; December palladium rose 2.25 dollars to
281 dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
December high-grade steel rose 1.4 cents to 75.05 cents a
pound. Copper futures also went up.
</P>
<P>
Greenspan, testifying before the U.S. Senate Budget Committee,
said that there was a need to "bring the existing instabilities to
a level of stability reasonably shortly to prevent the contagion
from really spilling over and creating some very significant
further difficulties for all of us."
</P>
<P>
Economists say Greenspan's comments were a strong signal that
Fed is considering taking actions to keep the American economy
strong in the face of a global economic crisis, and that the
central bank will cut interest rates when policy-makers meet next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources say that cutting interest rates could spur
home, auto and big-ticket sales, in which silver, platinum,
palladium and copper play key roles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Airlines Makes More Profits in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Airlines
(EAL) has made a net profit of 2.6 million U.S. Dollars in 1997,
8.6 percent more than the previous 1996, the monthly publication
"Airline Business" said in its September issue.
</P>
<P>
According to the publication, EAL's net profit has risen by
8.6 percent from 1996 although its total revenue went down to
257.5 million U.S. Dollars, 1.9 percent decrease from 1996.
</P>
<P>
EAL had a total of 750,000 passengers during 1997, a 2.7
percent increase from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to the publication, the airlines revenue from
passenger transport went up by 4.2 percent in 1997, while revenue
from cargo services increased by 7.4 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
It added that most of the profit gains came from "efficiency
and productivity improvements, rather than increases in
passengers and yields."
</P>
<P>
EAL, established in 1946, now has flights to Africa, Asia,
Europe and America with a total of 44 destinations worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
