<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Death Rate From Heart Disease Falls In U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A study released here
Wednesday said the risk of dying from heart disease dropped
remarkably in the United States in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by a group of researchers led by Wayne
Rosamoun of the University of North Carolina and published on the
latest issue of New England Journal of Medicine, looked at
statistics from regions of North Carolina, Mississippi, Minnesota
and Maryland between 1987 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
The study said that the deaths from heart disease fell 28
percent among men and 31 percent among women during the seven
years.
</P>
<P>
Researchers said the one-third drop of death rate in the United
States in recent years may be due largely to improvements in
treatment of heart attacks.
</P>
<P>
More people are taking drugs to control their cholesterol or
blood pressure, and more patients recognize the early warning
signs of heart attacks and get to hospitals, said Dr. Valentin
Fuster, president of the American Heart Association, adding that
the trend is toward overall improvement.
</P>
<P>
Heart attack is the leading cause of death in developed
countries. About 40 percent of all deaths in the United States
were due to heart disease in the past 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teenager Kournikova to Play Sanchez Vicario in Quarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian teenager Anna
Kournikova eliminated Wang Shi-ting of Chinese Taipei in straight
sets on Thursday, setting her quarterfinal clash against Arantxa
Sanchez Vicario in the Princess Cup tennis tournament.
</P>
<P>
The 17-year-old Russian, who reached the Wimbledon semi-finals
last season, surged to her victory with ease by scoring 6-0, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez Vicario, who paced Spain to beat Switzerland in the
Fed Cup last weekend, enjoyed her upperhands from the beginning
to seal the competition 6-0, 6-4 against Elena Likhovtseva of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Kournikova, who won the first set in 16 minutes, was broken in
her first serve to go down 0-2 in the second set, but rallied to
win the third and never faced a single break point throughout the
50-minute match.
</P>
<P>
The Russian teenager took every chance to charge to the net
and stunned the top player from Chinese Taipei with lightning
shots.
</P>
<P>
Regarding her next opponent, Kournikova was eager to avenge
her first defeat to Sanchez Vicario in the US Open fourth round
after beating her three times in a row on clay and hard court to
hold a 3-1 record.
</P>
<P>
"I've beaten her before on the same surface, so it doesn't
make any difference, but of course, I try to learn from mistakes
I did before. I just try to go out there, play my game and be
aggressive," said Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
For Sanchez Vicario, it was the first match since playing her
singles and doubles matches in beating Switzerland 3-2 in Geneva
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"It was very humid, so it was hard to hold the racket for a
while and swing a lot, but I'm happy with the way I played after
a long flight from Europe, not having so much time to recover,"
said the top seed, who needed 57 minutes to beat Likhovtseva.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Olga Barabanschikova of Belarus eliminated
fourth seed Dominique Van Roost of Belgium 3-6, 6-3, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Anke Huber of Germany earned the place against
Barabanschikova when she outclassed China's top player Li Fang,
7-5, 6-3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
