<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai GM Gets Huge Loan From Financial Consortium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A financial consortium
consisting of 39 Chinese and foreign banks signed an agreement
early this week to grant 821 million U.S. dollars in loans to
support the development of the automotive industry in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The loans will be used to build Shanghai General Motors Co.
(SGMC), a joint venture between the Shanghai Automobile Corp. and
General Motors of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The loan has lower financial charges than loans offered to
similar domestic projects, includes unsecured limited recourse
financing, and involves little risk, a bank official said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, the largest of its kind among commercial banks
in China, demonstrates Shanghai's ability to raise capital on both
the domestic and international market.
</P>
<P>
SGMC has registered capital of 700 million U.S. dollars, and
with this loan from the financial consortium, SGMC has now raised
enough money to complete its construction.
</P>
<P>
Rudy Schlais, President of GM China, expressed hopes that this
agreement will help SGMC develop into a world-class company.
</P>
<P>
SGMC, the largest-ever Sino-U.S. project, was established at
the beginning of last year in Shanghai's Pudong New Area. Its
first product, a Buick automobile, is scheduled to come off the
assembly line by the end of this year, and massive production is
expected to begin next April.  
</P>
</TEXT>
