<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Troops May Replace Norwegian Peacekeepers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 24 (Xinhua) -- With less than three months to
go before the Norwegian peace keepers depart from south Lebanon,
the Lebanese government is trying to persuade France to send
troops to replace them.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian government announced earlier this year that it
would be pulling its 625 troops out of south Lebanon in December
this year due to problems in attracting new recruits.
</P>
<P>
Several countries have been proposed as potential replacements,
including India, Nigeria, Ukraine and France.
</P>
<P>
An officer of the U.N. Interim Forces in Lebanon (UNIFIL) told
the Daily Star published on Thursday that Lebanon prefers French
troops to replace the outgoing Norwegians despite Indian
willingness to take part in the peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri has close ties with French
President Jacques Chirac and supports the growing role played by
Paris in the Middle East peace process, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
The officer said there was also an economic consideration in
choosing peacekeeping troops for the Lebanese government.
</P>
<P>
Some residents from Ibl es-Saqi, where the Norwegian battalion
headquarters is located, have reportedly asked Hariri to choose a
European country because their troops tend to be better paid and
have more spending power than their third world counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The residents have apparently warned the prime minister that
an economic downturn could prompt a mass exodus from the area if a
poorer nation replaces the Norwegians.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of local traders have a lucrative income from selling
all kinds of goods to UNIFIL troops.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong UNIFIL was established in 1978 after Israel's
first invasion of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
It was designed to help restore the Lebanese government's
authority over the southern part of the country and confirm the
Israeli withdrawal from the area.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 to allegedly protect its north from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
