<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers in Mao Zedong's Home Place Become Better Off (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The changes have been attributed to the move from the
decades-old planned economy to a market one. Farmers at Shaoshan,
where Mao was born on December 26, 1893, have developed a
diversified economy in accordance with market demands rather than
blindly growing rice and raising pigs as planned by the government.
</P>
<P>
The village has become a tourist resort in addition to a
memorial of the Communist-led revolution. Historic relics have
been restored and stone tablets with inscriptions of Mao's poetry
put up by villagers.
</P>
<P>
The village has attracted more than 14 million visitors from
all over, and in 1996, had an income of 100 million yuan, compared
with less than 60,000 yuan in the early 80s. Average annual
per-capita income is 5,200 yuan.
</P>
<P>
One unusual story is that of Shi Yinglian, who began running a
tannery eight years ago, lost 700,000 yuan in the first year owing
to lack of experience, and then finally succeeded after working
hard and learning more about technology, management and marketing.
</P>
<P>
Her factory now has 66 million yuan in output value and 2
million yuan in profits every year.
</P>
<P>
However, life for farmers in Xiangtan is still far from
luxurious, one city official points out, and a greater effort
needs to be made to have a more efficient rural economy in the
near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
