<HEADLINE> Sports Complex May Not Be Finished Before Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 24 (Xinhua) -- One of the major Asian Games
sports complexes may not be finished in time and alternate sites
for events may have to be found, local organizers said here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Bhichai Rattakul, chairman of the
Bangkok Asian Games Organizing Committee, said the liquidity
problems of the main contractor may prevent the company from
finishing the Muang Thong Thani complex in time for the Games
slated from December 6 to 20.
</P>
<P>
The committee will decide on Friday whether to move some of
the sports elsewhere. A statement from the committee said plans
had called for seven sports to be staged at the complex, which is
about 80 percent completed.
</P>
<P>
"I have no idea how to help," Bhichai was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Preparation for the games have been plagued by other problems
including political interference, alleged corruption and outright
incompetence.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Asian Games Organizing Committee threatened
several times to award Asia's biggest sports event to other
countries, but the Thais argued that all would be ready by the
opening day.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 athletes from 43 countries and regions are
expected to compete in the Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
