<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Raise Banks Reserves: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines said Thursday it will be forced to raise reserved
requirements for banks if the local currency, the peso, continues
to depreciate.
</P>
<P>
This was confirmed by Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson in
reaction to reports that the monetary system plans to introduce a
monetary measure that will sap up the excess liquidity in the
financial system.
</P>
<P>
Singson said he discussed the proposed measure with members of
the Monetary Board during a meeting Monday in order to cushion the
impact of the Philippine Airlines (PAL) row. PAL owes the local
banks some 9 billion pesos (202 million U.S. dollars), of which 7
billion pesos (157 million dollars) is fully collateralized.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that there is indeed an excess liquidity in the
banking system and that the only best solution to ward off
speculative activities would be to raise the banks' reserved
requirements.
</P>
<P>
Singson, however, declined to specify the amount of reserved
requirements to be imposed as this might create panic among
speculators.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that excess liquidity is taking place because the
number of people borrowing money from the banks has been minimized
due to high interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the peso came under attack when the negotiations
between the management of PAL and the striking workers bogged down
anew causing market volatility.
</P>
<P>
"What we are doing right now is to closely monitor the
performance of the peso against the dollar," Singson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
