<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas-funded Firms Encouraged to Increase Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province, China's
economic powerhouse and largest exporter, is encouraging
overseas-backed enterprises to increase their exports in a bid to
fulfill its projected export goals.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Governor Xu Deli announced some newly adopted favorable
policies for export-oriented foreign-funded businesses at a
meeting early this week, citing 322 excellent overseas-backed
firms including such multinationals as General Electric, DuPont,
Matsushita and Epson.
</P>
<P>
The new policies include cutting land-use taxes for the 322
listed businesses by 10 percent, imposing a low fee-levying
standard, with overseas-funded enterprises able to refuse to pay
any fee above the standard, and requiring customs to make things
more convenient for any overseas-funded firm exporting more than
10 million U.S. dollars worth of goods annually.
</P>
<P>
By the end of August, Guangdong had trade contacts with over 70
countries and regions, involving nearly 200,000 investment
contracts worth 198.3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The vice-governor said that Guangdong's 70,000 overseas-funded
enterprises play a decisive role in helping reach its exports goal
of expanding 10 to 15 percent this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
