<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Draws Up Post-Flood Rehabilitation Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi Water
Resources, Irrigation and Flood Control Ministry has chalked out a
post-flood rehabilitation plan involving 12.48 billion taka (265.5
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A total of 3.5 billion taka (74.5 million dollars) will be
required for a short-term program while 7.78 billion taka (165.5
million dollars) will be needed for a long-term one, in addition
to the 1.2 billion taka (25.5 million dollars) required for the
rehabilitation of some flood-damaged roads, The Independent daily
Thursday quoted a ministry official as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a perspective plan," he said. "It is a plan for
rehabilitation of the damaged infrastructure including
embankments, sluice gates, bridges, culverts, protection walls,
roads and groynes."
</P>
<P>
Due to the over-two-month-long floods, a total of 178
kilometers of embankments were totally damaged, while partial
damage was done to 1,586 kilometers of embankments in different
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 22 kilometers of protection walls were fully
damaged and another eight kilometers partially destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The assessment of the water resources ministry would be
submitted to the donors for their appraisal so as to provide
necessary help for the rehabilitation projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
The donors, particularly the World Bank and the Asian
Development Bank, have shown keen interest in financing the
rehabilitation programs, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
