<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Flock to Ningxia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region is emerging as a new haven for foreign investment in
northwest China.
</P>
<P>
In the first two days of the '98 Ningxia Trade Fair which took
place between September 18 and 22, a dozen overseas companies
invested in over 20 projects with local partners, involving 170
million U.S. dollars, which is 60 percent of the total overseas
investment Ningxia has attracted over the past 19 years.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure and agricultural projects were most favored by
overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
David Su, China head of the U.S.-based China Direct Inc., said
investors were mainly lured by Ningxia's rich natural resources
and preferential policies, such as five years exemption from duty
fees for solely overseas-funded enterprises.
</P>
<P>
His company has decided to invest 105 million U.S. dollars to
build two power plants with local partners.
</P>
<P>
The power plants will use local low-grade coal that is usually
discarded in large heaps, and this will also help clean up the
local environment.
</P>
<P>
The Eikem Group, one of the largest industrial enterprises in
Norway, plans to inject about 300 million yuan (36.14 million
U.S. dollars) into Ningxia over the next four to five years to
develop carbon-based products.
</P>
<P>
And Hong Kong investors will help build the first expressway in
Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
The Chines government has decided to accelerate economic
development in the vast western region of the country where ther
are rich natural and human resources.
</P>
<P>
A series of preferential policies have been worked out to this
end.  
</P>
