<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burkina Faso, Ghana to Foster Military Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Ghana and Burkina Faso have
said there is need for the two neighbors to foster military
cooperation among Africa countries to help solved conflicts on
the continent, Ghana News Agency (GNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Burkinese Defense Minister Milogo-De Albert, who led a
six-man military delegation to Accra#,Ghana's capital, agreed
Wednesday with his Ghanaian counterpart Iddrisu Mahama that most
of the conflicts plaguing the continent could have been resolved
long ago if African governments exchanged programs through their
military institutions.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, including Colonel Ibrahim Traore, Burkinese
Chief of Defense Staff (CDS), arrived in the country Tuesday for
a five-day visit.
</P>
<P>
The Burkinese delegation will hold discussions with their
Ghanaian counterparts on bilateral issues to help strengthen the
long-standing friendly relations between Ghana and Burkina Faso
which dates back to 1984.
</P>
<P>
Albert said following the visit to Ghana by President Blaise
Campaore, there was the need for a follow-up to enable the two
countries to discuss "areas where we can organize our military
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Ouagadougou is particularly interested in the training of
military officers in the two sister countries for common
operations and hoped both nations will start this through
exchange programs for other African countries to emulate.
</P>
<P>
The Burkinese defense minister suggested that one way by
which African governments can help bring lasting peace onto the
continent is by inculcating the principle of unity in their youth
through exchange programs.
</P>
<P>
"If our children are trained together in the same colleges,
it will be difficult for them to fight one another."
</P>
<P>
Welcoming his Burkinese counterpart, Alhaji Iddrisu expressed
concern about the lack of confidence and trust among African
governments, and hoped with strengthened joint commissions for
cooperation African governments will eliminate those fears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
