<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Reinforcing Dykes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu
Province, one of the country's economic powerhouses and a region
threatened by Yangtze River floods, plans to reinforce its major
dykes this winter and next spring.
</P>
<P>
Provincial Governor Zheng Silin said his government will put
this task at the top of the agenda for 1999 to ensure completion
of the project before the next flood season.
</P>
<P>
Government investment in water control projects will be raised
from the previous 2.5 billion yuan to 3.5 billion yuan, and
additional funds will be raised through various channels,
including state bonds and bank loans, Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
The project includes building 700 kilometers of river
revetments and 348 kilometers of breakwaters.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu now has 1,500 kilometers of river dykes, and the
provincial government plans to allocate 2.5 billion yuan to
fortify and heighten them over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Jiangsu reinforced 635 kilometers of embankments,
built 335 kilometers of stone slopes, and repaired 256 dangerous
culvert water gates. These measures are believed to have reduced
flood-related losses by 20 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, China's largest industrial center at the mouth of
the Yangtze River, has three-year plan to consolidate its
dykes and seawalls so they can also withstand rare typhoons.
</P>
<P>
This reinforcement plan will cost an estimated 700 million
yuan and is scheduled to be completed before June, 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's C. Bank Rejects Cutting Cash Ratio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya
(CBK) has turned down a request by small banks, threatened with a
run by depositors, to reduce the cash ratio requirement currently
at 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
In rejecting the request, CBK said it could not operate a
different regime for small and big banks, the Daily Nation
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The cash ratio refers to the amount of money that banks must
deposit with the CBK from the deposits collected from the public
where it stays without earning interest. It is one of the tools
that CBK uses to check money supply.
</P>
<P>
Three commercial banks -- Reliance Bank, Trust Bank and
Bullion Bank -- have been put under statutory management by CBK
in the past two weeks, causing a panic among small and medium
sized banks in the country.
</P>
<P>
Over the weekend, representatives of 20 small commercial banks
came together to start a fund to assist any of the members that
may face a liquidity crisis.
</P>
<P>
They also said at a meeting with CBK this week that they
agreed with CBK over the need to raise the share capital or to
merge to strengthen the banking sector.
</P>
<P>
The banks, led by Manu Chandaria, a leading industrialist, is
now seeking CBK's guidance on the modalities of managing the fund
and possibilities of additional help from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
However, a survey showed that most banks were cautiously
optimistic about their future.
</P>
<P>
Some banks were also taking steps to avoid panic withdrawals
by depositors by putting a ceiling on the amount of money that
depositors can withdraw at any one time.
</P>
<P>
There are a total of 55 banks and financial institutions in
this east African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
