<HEADLINE> Russia to Fund Ukrainian Nuclear Power Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Russia will offer 180 million
U.S. dollars next year to help Ukraine build two nuclear power
stations, Ukraine President Leonid Kuchma has announced here.
</P>
<P>
He told local reporters that during his talks with Russian
leaders in Moscow on September 18 and 19, Russia agreed to set
aside 180 million dollars from its next year's budget to fund the
building of the Rovno station and the Khmelynitsky station.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Ukraine would go ahead with the projects with
the cooperation from Russia, no matter whether the European Bank
of Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) would extend its promised
fund of 750 million dollars to the stations.
</P>
<P>
In April 1996, the Group of Seven and the European Union signed
an agreement with Ukraine in Moscow on shutting down the Chernobyl
station, one of whose reactors exploded in April 1986, killing and
wounding thousands of people with its leaked radioactivity.
</P>
<P>
The Western countries promised to fund the building of the two
new nuclear power stations in exchange for the shutdown of the
Chernobyl station.
</P>
<P>
The two stations are near completion, but building has stopped
because of shortage of Western fund.
</P>
<P>
Analysts see the Russian move to offer aid to Ukraine while
itself is suffering an economic crisis as a friendly gesture to
its neighbor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
