<HEADLINE> 80,000 Cubans Evacuated Before Arrival of Hurricane George </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 80,000 people have been
evacuated from five southeastern Cuban provinces, where a state of
emergency was declared before the expected arrival of hurricane
"George" Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Helicopters and amphibious vehicles of the armed forces are
standing by to provide transportation for evacuees and relief
materials, official reports said.
</P>
<P>
The five provinces are Guantanamo, Holguin, Santiago de Cuba,
Las Tunas and Granma.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Castro Wednesday inspected the headquarters of
the Meteorology Institute, which has been closely following the
course of the hurricane, now classified as a "one" on the
Saffir-Simpson scale of "five."
</P>
<P>
Castro said the Cuban authorities were prepared to face the
worst in case of a variation in the movement of the hurricane
toward the northern coast of the island.
</P>
<P>
Damage is expected to the country's sugar and coffee sectors,
as well as the been and rice production, which has already been
affected by a severe drought earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane "George" has so far reportedly left almost 20 dead on
its way through the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
The latest report of the Meteorology Institute said "George"
was going to penetrate the Cuban territory on Wednesday night
through the city of Guantanamo, some 1,000 kilometers east of
Havana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
