<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Major Athletics Doping Scandals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Following are the chronology
of major athletics doping scandals since Ben Johnson tested
positive at the 1988 Seoul Olympic Games:
</P>
<P>
September 27, 1988: Johnson was stripped of 100-meter Olympic
gold medal and banned for two years for positive test of steroid
stanozolol.
</P>
<P>
June 1989: Johnson admitted that he had taken steroids since
1981.
</P>
<P>
September 1989: Johnson was stripped of 1987 100-meter world
record.
</P>
<P>
November 1990: World 400-meter record holder Harry "Butch"
Reynolds was suspended for two years after postive tests for
steroids.
</P>
<P>
January 1991: Johnson returned to track at the end of ban.
</P>
<P>
June 1991: Reynolds competed in U.S. trials in defiance of ban.
</P>
<P>
February 1992: Double world champion Katrin Krabbe was banned
for four years for tampering with urine samples in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
April 1992: German panel lifted ban on Krabbe, citing
irregularities in testing procedure.
</P>
<P>
May 1992: IAAF arbitration panel upheld suspension on Reynolds
who later filed a lawsuit of 12.5 million dollars against IAAF.
</P>
<P>
June 1992: U.S. Supreme Court ruled Reynolds could run in
trials who later made the Olympic team as alternate in 4X400
relay; IAAF decided not to ban Krabbe because of legal problems
with case.
</P>
<P>
July 1992-August 1992: News of doping clouded the Barcelona
Olympic Games with British sprinter Jason Livingston failed test
before the Games, Krabbe tested positive for clebunterol, all
three medallists in the men's shot put served drugs bans.
</P>
<P>
September 1992: Krabbe was banned for four years.
</P>
<P>
December 1992: U.S. federal court ruled that IAAF should pay
Reynolds 27.3 million dollars in compensation.
</P>
<P>
January 1993: IAAF set Reynolds a one-month deadline to stop
legal action.
</P>
<P>
March 1993: German athletics federation's ban on Krabbe
reduced to one year; Johnson banned for life for positive test of
testosterone in Montreal; Reynolds returned to compete indoor
worlds by the end of ban.
</P>
<P>
August 1993: IAAF decided to ban Krabbe for further two years.
</P>
<P>
October 1994: Reynolds lost Supreme Court appeal after the
Federation appeals court reversed in May the ruling of the lower
court which granted him 27.3 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
March 1996: Krabbe was granted right to demand compensation
from IAAF but has already given up her career.
</P>
<P>
July 1997: IAAF decided to revert to two years for minimum
drug bans because of legal complications in many countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
