<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Ranks First As News Source in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A nationwide survey reveals
that TV has become the most important news source in China,
followed by newspapers and radio, according to today's
Shanghai-based Wenhui Daily.
</P>
<P>
The survey was jointly conducted by China Central Television
(CCTV) and 16 provincial and city-level TV stations, the third
such sample survey taken, the others having been conducted in 1987
and 1992.
</P>
<P>
A total of 16,066 people above the age of 13 answered the
survey.
</P>
<P>
Result show that China now has 1.094 billion television
viewers, the largest group in the world, with 317 million TV sets
in all, both color and black-and-white.
</P>
<P>
Urban residents on average can receive 15 different channels,
and in some major cities more than 20, while rural farmers usually
have access to 6 channels. Some 34.5 percent of Chinese families
now have cable television.
</P>
<P>
Most of people surveyed said they are interested in news report
more than entertainment programs. "We want to know what is
happening at home and abroad and get a better understanding of
state principles and polices," one said.
</P>
<P>
Serial plays and programs related to law and sports have their
own relatively stable viewer groups, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
It also found the average Chinese spends two hours and 11
minutes watching TV each day, and they usually watch longer
on weekends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Minister to Contest Sri Lankan Presidential Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- A former powerful minister in
the previous government, Sirisena Cooray, has expressed his
intention to contest Sri Lanka's next presidential election as an
independent candidate.
</P>
<P>
The election is due in two years' time, but it may be held
earlier if the present incumbent, Chandrika Kumaratunga, so
decides.
</P>
<P>
Cooray said at a meeting of his supporters here recently that
he will contest the election as an independent candidate and he
will win. he said running for president as an independent would be
better than representing a political party.
</P>
<P>
Several former MPs and former municipal councilors from the now
main opposition party United National Party (UNP) were also
present at the meeting, UNP sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the UNP, of which he was a member, had urged
him to take up full-time politics, the sources pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Cooray said he would not let them down.
</P>
<P>
While he does not seek positions he is very keen on pushing
forward the policies initiated by former President Ranasighe
Premadasa, he said. And that is why he is keen on returning to
politics.
</P>
<P>
Former President Premadasa was killed in a powerful bomb blast
by Tamil rebels on May 1, 1993. 
</P>
