<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian Assembly In Session in Siem Reap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SIEM REAP, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The 122 new lawmakers,
along with diplomats and some dignitaries, attended the opening
ceremony of the new National Assembly in Siem Reap Thursday at the
residence of King Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
Second Prime Minister and Vice-President of Cambodian People's
Party (CPP) Hun Sen, Prince Ranariddh of the Funcinpec party, and
Sam Rainsy of the Sam Rainsy Party (SRP) all attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia held a National Assembly election on July
26. Thirty-nine political parties, 19 more than in the
UN-administered election in 1993, were vying for 122 parliamentary
seats and the right to form a new government.
</P>
<P>
The previous National Assembly of 120 members was elected five
years ago and its tenure expired on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's Assembly is a unicameral body with at least 120
members who are elected every five years by universal direct adult
suffrage. The current Assembly members will be sworn in later at
Angkor Wat, the famous ancient Khmer temple.
</P>
<P>
The ruling CPP of Second Prime Minister Hun Sen won 64 seats in
the election, followed by Prince Ranariddh's Funcinpec Party with
43 seats and Sam Rainsy's self named SRP with 15 seats.
</P>
<P>
A coalition is necessary because, while the CPP has a majority
in parliament, it lacks the two-thirds needed to form a government
of its own.
</P>
<P>
But the opposition Funcinpec party and its ally, the SRP, which
won the remainder of the seats, had boycotted the election results
and the Assembly, claiming there was serious election fraud and
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
King Sihanouk stepped in to defuse the crisis when weeks of
opposition anti-Hun Sen protests in the capital erupted into
violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
