<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Calls for India's Medium-Term Fiscal Adjustment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 24 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) has asked India to launch a medium-term fiscal
adjustment program at both central and state levels and initiate
steps to revive investment and growth.
</P>
<P>
"Reviving the fiscal reform process would help lower real
interest rates, improve debt dynamics, create room for meeting
essential social and infrastructure spending and reduce the drag
on growth," the IMF Executive Board said in its assessment of the
Indian economy.
</P>
<P>
Unproductive expenditures must be cut by curtailing subsidies,
reducing public sector employment and improving cost recovery and
public expenditure management, the paper The Observer of Business
and Politics Thursday quoted the IMF as saying.
</P>
<P>
The IMF cautioned against the Indian government's strategy of
orienting fiscal and monetary policies toward supporting domestic
demand as it could further strain macroeconomic stability.
</P>
<P>
Expressing concern about the lack of any perceptible fiscal
adjustment by various states in India, the IMF stressed that the
states would need to intensify and broaden efforts to lower
deficits and also improve the composition of spending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
