<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, September 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME -- Italy's economy will only see a 1.7 percent growth rate
this year, down from the earlier forecast of 2.3 percent, a
leading research institute predicted on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Prometeia Research Institute was more pessimistic about
growth figures in gross domestic product (GDP) for 1999, revising
its pre-summer forecast of a 2.6 percent increase in GDP to 2.3
percent. (Italy-Economy-Forecast)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso vowed
on Wednesday to defend the stability of the national currency, the
real, in face of financial crisis in southeast Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Brazilian people know I will do whatever is necessary to
protect the real, to defend the purchase power of salaried people,
in order to lower interest rates and take once again the road of
growth," he said at the Itamaraty Palace, seat of the country's
Foreign Ministry. (Brazil-President-Currency)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PARIS -- The crisis hit Asian economy should begin to recover
in 2000 or 2001, International Monetary Fund chief Michel
Camdessus predicted here Wednesday,
</P>
<P>
Camdessus, the managing director of the IMF, told French radio
that for several Asian countries, excluding Japan, "the worst has
passed". (IMF-Asia-Camdessus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- Brazil has lost 28.6 billion U.S. dollars
from its national reserves since early August 1998, the newspaper
O Jornal do Brasil reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the capital loss in August totaled 12
billion dollars, due to the influence of the international
financial crisis and the devaluation of Russian currency.
(Brazil-Capital Flow)
</P>
