<HEADLINE> Italian Senators Hail Great Changes in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Tibetans enjoy broad religious
freedom and their living standards have been raised considerably,
an Italian parliamentary delegation said here at the Senate on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The five-member delegation, which ended a 10-day visit last
month, were announcing the findings of their report on their
experiences in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"From what we saw and heard, we can say some Westerners' worry
about Tibet is groundless," said delegation leader Senator Renzo
Gubert.
</P>
<P>
Great changes had taken place since 1959 with industry
developing steadily and construction of highways, airports,
hospitals and schools, he added.
</P>
<P>
"Tibetans enjoy total religious freedom and we saw many people
going to the monasteries without restrictions." he said.
</P>
<P>
Tibet enjoyed more autonomy than other provinces, and about 70
percent of the administrators were Tibetans, he added.
</P>
<P>
It was baseless to say Tibet was now dominated by the Han
people, he argued.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government strongly opposed Tibetan independence,
he noted, but it always kept its doors open to dialogue with
the religious leader, the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
"Our delegation is the third of its kind from European
countries which have visited Tibet, this very fact shows that the
Chinese government is open on the issue of Tibet. They welcome
foreigners to Tibet," he added.
</P>
<P>
Delegation member Senator Roberto Lasagna said that their
observations could help them avoid making a wrong judgement on
China.
</P>
<P>
They knew the belief that the Chinese government invaded Tibet
in 1959 was wrong, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said Tibetan culture was well protected and it was
absolutely untrue that Tibetan culture had suffered irreparable
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Lasagna, a physician by profession, also noted that traditional
Tibetan medicine was also well protected and patients had freedom
to choose whether they used traditional or western medicine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
