<HEADLINE> Clinton Speaks to Congressional Hispanic Caucus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton got a warm expression of support from the Congressional
Hispanic Caucus Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton received two extended standing ovations Wednesday night
when he addressed the Congressional Hispanic Caucus Institute's
annual black-tie gala at a Washington hotel.
</P>
<P>
"Thank you for that warm welcome," Clinton said. "But as happy
as I am -- and grateful -- for the reception you gave me, that's
not what this is about. It's about you and your children."
</P>
<P>
Clinton's speech came just two days after his videotaped grand
jury testimony in the Monica Lewinsky investigation was televised
and four days after he received a similar warm welcome at the
annual dinner of the Congressional Black Caucus.
</P>
<P>
In his address Clinton offered his views on issues of
importance to Hispanics such as bilingual education, immigration,
a minimum wage increase, the use of sampling in the 2000 census, a
referendum on statehood or independence for Puerto Rico and using
the projected budget surplus for preserving Social Security
instead of cutting taxes.
</P>
<P>
The dinner culminated a two-day legislative conference in which
members of the caucus addressed many of the issues Clinton
mentioned in his speech. The president said the Hispanic caucus
deserved a large share of the credit for many of his
administration's accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the caucus "for being my friend, for standing with
me on sunny days and in strong winds." Vice President Al Gore also
addressed the group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
