<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Tightens Security at Water Treatment Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has tightened
security at its main water treatment plant at Amabatale following
security reports that sketches of the plant had been found with
the a Tamil rebel suspect who had been arrested.
</P>
<P>
Vice Chairman of the National Water Supply Board S. B. Boyagane
Wednesday evening said only the relevant resource personnel of the
board had been allowed to make use of such sketches only when
required, the Daily News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
No outsider had access to these, he noted.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the rebels had purchased sewerage maps
from board employees at exorbitant rates.
</P>
<P>
Consequently the board has drawn up a security dragnet in
consultation with the security establishment.
</P>
<P>
A sophisticated electronic surveillance radio system have been
installed in 17 sewerage pumping stations in Colombo city which
are electronically linked to the vital security installation,
Boyagane said.
</P>
<P>
He added that this should be adequate to prevent a hazard.
</P>
</TEXT>
