<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Relaxes Rules on Export With Laos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Thai and Lao customs
officials have agreed to ease third-party export procedures to
help boost trade between the two countries, the newspaper Bangkok
Post said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
To ease procedures and expedite trade, officials agreed to cut
the number of product categories requiring prior approval and
screening for re-export from five to two.
</P>
<P>
Cigarette and liquor will continue to require special
examination and documentation for reshipment. Electric goods, gold
and watches have been removed from the list.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, goods worth 9.86 billion baht
(246.5 million U.S. dollars) were re-exported to Laos through
Thailand last year, an increase of 15 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
For the first six months of this year, goods exported through
Thailand to Laos totaled 6.86 billion baht (171.5 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Officials said such trade is expected to increase in the
future. Most goods sent to Laos through Thailand originate from
other countries in the region, such as Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Thai officials said special examination is needed to ensure
that goods coming into the country for reshipment are actually
re-exported to Laos, rather than consumed by the local market and
thus result in a loss of tax revenue for both countries.
</P>
<P>
As the two countries agreed, Lao officials will issue
certificates of landing to Thai custom officials once goods enter
Laos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0251 </DOCNO>
