<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Western China Faces Fourth Development Opportunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Western China is expecting
its fourth opportunity for development, with attention focused on
developing a knowledge-based economy with the cooperation of
foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Michel Oksenberg, a Chinese affairs specialist and professor at
Stanford University, made this remark at a symposium on
Sino-U.S. Intellectual Property Rights and Economic Development in
southwest China's Chongqing Municipality recently.
</P>
<P>
He said that though the development of China's coastal areas is
important, history has demonstrated that the coastal area
cannot independently guarantee the prosperity, stability and
unity of the country.
</P>
<P>
The western regions of China have played a very important role
in the development of the country ever since the Warring States
Period (475 B.C.-221 B.C).
</P>
<P>
He said western China has witnessed three strategic
developments during the 20th century: the first in the 1940s when
military industries were set up in the southwest and northwest,
enabling China to win the War of Resistance Against Japan; the
second occurred during the first Five-Year Plan period
(1953-1957) when China shifted many important industries to inland
areas; and the third was the relocation of many national defence
enterprises into inland areas in the 1960s and 70s.
</P>
<P>
Oksenberg has been studying China since the 1960s and has
written books including "China: The Convulsive Society," "China
and America: Past and Future," "Policy Making in China: Leaders,
Structure, and Process" and "China's Participation in the IMF,
the World Bank, and GATT: Toward a Global Economic Order."
</P>
<P>
He said China now is making greater efforts to develop the
western part of the country. What is different from the previous
three developments is that China now aims to make its development
a part of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
He said economic growth and development still have a way to go,
and that foreign trade, foreign investment and foreign
technological transfer stimulated China's economic growth, which
has been faster in the coastal areas than the inland areas. An the
inland areas have developed faster than the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, China's inland areas have many
advantages such as a profound traditional culture, rich natural
resources and higher bank savings deposits. So there is every
reason for the world to have confidence in the development of
western China, he concluded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to Implement CTBT Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Affairs
Minister Lloyd Axworthy announced Wednesday that his government
has tabled legislation to implement the Comprehensive Nuclear Test
Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
The legislation, called the CTBT Implementation Act, will allow
Canada to maintain its leadership in nuclear non-proliferation and
disarmament issues by being among the first to ratify the treaty,
according to a government news release.
</P>
<P>
"The Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty establishes a global
norm against nuclear testing for all nations, even those that may
not immediately join," Axworthy was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, signed by Canada in September 1996, recognizes that
halting all nuclear test explosions is an effective measure to
nuclear disarmament and non-proliferation.
</P>
<P>
The new act authorizes Canadian government departments, such as
foreign affairs and international trade institutions, to carry out
tasks required under the treaty, according to the release.
</P>
<P>
The act prohibits persons from causing, encouraging or
participating in a nuclear weapon test explosion or any other
nuclear explosion for purposes of developing nuclear weapons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0255 </DOCNO>
