<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar Promotes Agricultural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar is an agro-based
country with its agricultural production contributing 36 percent
of the national gross domestic product (GDP) and 35 percent of the
export.
</P>
<P>
About 11.51 million people or 62.68 percent of the total
employees in the country's productive sectors are engaged in
agricultural activities.
</P>
<P>
As the agriculture sector is the mainstay of the country's
economy, the government has been taking various measures to boost
the sector's development.
</P>
<P>
As increase of investment is vital for agricultural
development, the government has been investing more in the sector
over the years.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official statistics, the total
agricultural investment in the 1997-98 fiscal year, which ended in
March, amounted to 116 million U.S. dollars, 36 million dollars
more than the previous year and 107 million dollars more than the
previous five years.
</P>
<P>
The government disbursed agricultural loans of 1.75 billion
dollars to farmers in the year, rising by 100 million dollars over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
To enable farmers to grow in time the state-needed seasonal
industrial crops, the government also gives advance payment to the
farmers every year.
</P>
<P>
The government also has introduced foreign investment into the
sector since opening the country's door to the outside world in
late 1988, getting 14.35 million dollars by the end of June this
year.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has expanded cultivated land with sown area under crops
reaching 12.51 million hectares in the 1997-98 fiscal year,
189,540 hectares more than the previous year. In this respect, the
country also leased out a total of 14,692 hectares of land to 108
private enterprises in the year, increasing by 8,297 hectares over
the previous year.
</P>
<P>
To ensure harvest in agriculture, Myanmar has increased
building of irrigation facilities which are vital for
agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
A total of 90 such facilities including dams and reservoirs
have been built since 1988, irrigating nearly 546,750 hectares.
</P>
<P>
To give farmers incentives in farming, the government has
raised purchasing prices for their agricultural products
especially paddy, one of the four main crops in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
In the two decades between the 1950s and the 1960s, the price
of paddy remained at 60 dollars per 100 baskets (2,090 kilograms).
The price began rising in the 1970s, reaching 150 dollars and has
kept on soaring in the last few years, to the present 250 dollars.
</P>
<P>
On technical cultivation, the government pays special attention
to research on high quality yield of crops, carrying out
experiment on local and foreign quality seeds. Other related
techniques are also disseminated to farmers.
</P>
<P>
In this respect, Myanmar began in April implementation of a
five-year seed bank project in Yezin, central Pyinmana, with the
aid of Japan under the two countries' technical cooperation
program.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is also cooperating with foreign countries in the
development of its agriculture sector. It reached agreement with
neighboring India on the exchange of quality strains and sending
of Myanmar trainees to research centers and universities in India
and of delegations for the development of agricultural techniques.
</P>
<P>
To mechanize its agriculture, Myanmar has been encouraging
farmers to widely use both locally-produced and imported
agricultural implements, establishing so far 23 model mechanized
agricultural villages in the country.
</P>
<P>
To boost mechanization, the country's manufacturing sector is
also giving first priority to the production of farm machinery
and equipment, designating agricultural implements as one of the
14 first-priority goods for import.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the measures taken, Myanmar's agriculture grew by 2.9
percent in output value in the 1997-98 fiscal year despite flash
floods and drought during the fiscal year in some areas. The
country's paddy production in the year was 17.3 million tons, up
from 14.8 million tons in the 1992-93 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
