<HEADLINE> Clinton, Singaporean PM Discuss Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Singaporean Prime Minister
Goh Chok Tong and U.S. President Bill Clinton met at the White
House on Wednesday, focusing on the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
They discussed capital controls and the situation in Indonesia,
one of the Asian countries suffering from the financial meltdown
that began in Thailand in the summer of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"We focused on the Asian financial crisis that's on everybody's
mind," Goh told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He warned other countries in the region against following
Malaysia's decision to impose capital controls, saying this was a
short-term solution.
</P>
<P>
"There's a danger some countries may begin to have capital
controls. Malaysia has started and others may follow suit if the
Malaysian way of managing the economic problems succeeds in the
short-term," Goh said.
</P>
<P>
"The danger is whether the short-term management of a problem
becomes long term. We discussed all that," he added.
</P>
<P>
Goh said he and Clinton also discussed the Asian-Pacific
Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum meeting scheduled for November
in Malaysia. 
</P>
