<HEADLINE> Chinese Chess Players Leave for Olympiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Former world champion Xie
Jun spearheaded the Chinese chess delegation to compete in the
33rd Chess Olympiad slated for September 26 in Elista, Russia.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese delegation was to leave here Thursday for the
biennial chess gala which saw the first men's tournament
inaugurated in 1927 and the women's edition initiated 30 years
later.
</P>
<P>
The four-member Chinese women delegation fields in the same
squad that won the silver medal in the last Olympiad, which
includes, apart from women's world champion Xie Jun, twice world
junior champion Zhu Cheng, candidate for world champion
challenger Wang Pin and Universiade champion Wang Lei.
</P>
<P>
Although they lag behind reigning champion Georgia and third
place finisher Russia in ranking points, the Chinese women
players still aim to snatch the world title by vowing to play to
their best.
</P>
<P>
In the men's tournament, China dispatches its youngest squad
since its first attendance in 1978 with an average age of 24 for
the Olympiad.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese men squad has three international grand masters
Peng Xiaomin, Zhang Zhong and Ye Jiangchuan who also serves as
coach of former world champion Xie Jun, two international masters
Wu Wenjin and Yu Shaoteng and master Wang Rui.
</P>
<P>
Among the Chinese men players, Wu Wenjin, Yu Shaoteng and Wang
Rui will make their debuts in the coming Olympiad, hoping to
fully display their witts and gutts to achieve satisfactory
scores in the world chess arena.
</P>
<P>
The Chess Olympiad is the highest and largest international
meet chaired by the International Chess Federation, with the
registration of competitors from 122 countries and regions for
the showcase of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Olympiad will run from September 26 to October 12 for 14
rounds under the Swiss system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
