<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Say China's Flooding Caused By Worsening Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists say that
the catastrophic flooding in China this summer was caused by
global climate changes and damage to the ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
The excessive felling of trees along the upper reaches of the
Yangtze River for the past several decades has led to soil erosion
in the area along the river and can be blamed for the flooding of
the past three months.
</P>
<P>
Dongting Lake, a natural reservoir for the Yangtze River in
Hunan Province, has become 40 percent smaller since the 1950s as a
result of silting, and government officials and researchers
believe that it's high time for China to put more emphasis on
environmental protection after having studied the flood-ravaged
areas.
</P>
<P>
Yangtze River Resources Committee researchers say that another
important factor is global climate changes, for which humans are
responsible.
</P>
<P>
As global industrialization speeds up, air pollution becomes
worse and the greenhouse effect, solar activities, and ozone layer
impairment have caused more frequent El Nino and La Nina
occurrences, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
Chao Jiping, a Chinese Academy of Sciences oceanographer, says
that China's devastating floods were closely related to these
phenomena. Last year's El Nino was the strongest of this century,
and high barometric pressure from subtropical areas moved westward
into China instead of leaving for the south early this spring,
bringing extra precipitation in southern China.
</P>
<P>
As a consequence, the lowest water level on the Yangtze River,
near Wuhan in January, was 3.47 metres higher than the average,
according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
In July, the La Nina phenomenon came immediately after El Nino,
preventing the high barometric pressure zone from moving
northward, and bringing additional precipitation.
</P>
<P>
China is affected by Pacific monsoons, and the plateau in
southwestern China keeps away climate moderations from the Indian
Ocean, making China a victim of global climate changes, scientists
say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
