<HEADLINE> Transit Passengers to Be Allowed Outside Bangkok Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 24 (Xinhua) -- From October 1, 1998, transit
passengers eligible for visa-free entry and visa-on-arrival will
be able to travel out of Bangkok Airport for up to 12 hours,
according to the Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT).
</P>
<P>
The passengers will be exempted from paying the 500-baht
(12.5-U.S. dollar) passenger service charge when they check in for
their onward connecting flight, said TAT in a press release
available Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to yield a bonanza of at least 1 billion
baht (25 million dollars) a year to the government treasury if
each transit traveler spends only 500 baht during their stopover.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, a total of 2,147,567 passengers changed flights at
Bangkok's Don Muang International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Though most of them catch onward flights within a few hours, a
sizable number transit for six hours or more, which is normally
enough for them to take a quick tour of the city.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Thai Travel Agents has outlined several tour
programs for transfer tourists to enjoy, such as shopping tour,
scenic city guide or health and beauty tours.
</P>
<P>
The procedures for transit passengers to go out of the airport
are also easy, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
They need only to fill a Passenger Service Charge Exempt
Requesting Form at service units and present it with their
passport, airline ticket and completed arrival/departure card, to
obtain an official stamp before passing immigration at arrival
points.
</P>
<P>
These documents should be kept and presented again upon the
passengers' departure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
