<HEADLINE> Italy's Economic Growth to Slow Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Italy's economy will only see a
1.7 percent growth rate this year, down from the earlier forecast
of 2.3 percent, a leading research institute predicted on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Prometeia Research Institute was more pessimistic about
growth figures in gross domestic product (GDP) for 1999, revising
its pre-summer forecast of a 2.6 percent increase in GDP to 2.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Prometeia figures, which will be officially released early
next week, represent the most pessimistic estimates so far but
follow the heels of other GDP forecast revisions.
</P>
<P>
On September 9, Prime Minister Romano Prodi issued a government
forecast indicating a two percent increase in GDP, compared to the
2.5 percent contained in the government's three-year Economic and
Financial Planning Document released in the spring.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the employer's association, Confindustria,
revised its forecast down from 2.3 percent to 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the most gloomy forecast up until Prometeia's was issued by
the retailers' association, Confcommercio, which put growth at 1.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown has been attributed to the impact of the Asian and
Russian economic crises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
