<HEADLINE> U.S. Lawmakers Approve Defense Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. House and Senate
negotiators on Wednesday approved a 250.5-billion-U.S.-dollar
defense spending plan, which is smaller than what President Bill
Clinton and some Republican lawmakers had called for.
</P>
<P>
The spending approved by the lawmakers is 2.8 billion dollars
above the current levels but 485 million dollars below a White
House request.
</P>
<P>
The approval was made after a closed session to work out
differences between House and Senate defense spending plans for
the new fiscal year that starts October 1.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill -- which accounts for about 15 percent of the
total federal spending -- 70.6 billion dollars would be provided
for military personnel, including a 3.6 percent pay raise; 84
billion dollars for operations and maintenance; and 48.5 billion
dollars for purchasing new weapons and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, President Clinton asked Congress to give the
Pentagon an extra one billion dollars next year to cover spare
parts shortages and other readiness problems and to bolster
long-term budgets to update weapons and keep top-quality personnel.
</P>
<P>
Congress, before adjourning for the year in early October, is
expected to act on legislation to cover unforeseen military
expenses, such as 1.9 billion dollars for peacekeeping operations
in Bosnia and more than one billion dollars for Year 2000 military
computers fixes.
</P>
<P>
The full House and Senate will vote on the plan before Congress
adjourns. 
</P>
