<HEADLINE> Asian Economy to Recover in 2000, Predicts IMF Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The crisis hit Asian economy
should begin to recover in 2000 or 2001, International Monetary
Fund chief Michel Camdessus predicted here Wednesday,
</P>
<P>
Camdessus, the managing director of the IMF, told French radio
that for several Asian countries, excluding Japan, "the worst has
passed".
</P>
<P>
"Economic growth would already have begun to recover if we had
not had a crisis at the heart of the crisis, which is the Japanese
crisis," he added.
</P>
<P>
Japan was set for recovery in the second half of next year, but
its economy was likely to shrink by 2.5 percent or more this year,
he predicted.
</P>
<P>
Camdessus said Europe is likely to grow slightly less quickly
in 1999 than this year, with an average growth rate of two to
three percent next year.
</P>
<P>
The Group of Seven (G7) countries should play the role of the
engine of world growth because the United States and Europe were
doing well when the rest of the world was in trouble, he added.
</P>
<P>
Turning specifically to Russia, he said the IMF would support
Moscow only if the new Russian cabinet led by Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov restored the ruble and budget to health and
restructured frozen domestic debt in a "civilized" way for
creditors.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has suspended all its loan programs, worth 12.5 billion
U.S. dollars this year alone, to Russia until the new government
explains how it plans to steer the country out of the acute
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The IMF was established in December 1945 to promote
international monetary cooperation, to facilitate the expansion
and balanced growth of international trade and promote stability
in foreign trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
