<HEADLINE> Finnish Official Suspected of Spying for Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A Finnish Foreign Ministry
official is suspected of providing Russia with confidential
information on the European Union (EU) and has been removed from
his post, the ministry said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Two diplomats at the Russian embassy in Helsinki, who are
believed to be the recipients of the unspecified documents, left
Finland at the end of the summer. One left voluntarily and the
other was encouraged to do so, said Foreign Ministry
Undersecretary Jukka Valtasaari.
</P>
<P>
But the identify of the suspected ministry official, who is
under questioning, has not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Finnish European Affairs Minister Ole Norrback called the
matter "serious", but said the image of Finland as an EU member
would not be hurt.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, the Russian Foreign Ministry expressed "bewilderment
and regret", and urged Helsinki to reconsider its decision.
</P>
<P>
Finland, which will take the rotating chairmanship of the EU on
July 1, 1999, is the only EU country to share a border with
Russia. 
</P>
