<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmer-Operated Inns Springing Up in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Nowadays foreign travelers no
longer worry about where to pass a warm night in the countryside
of the Tibet Autonomous Region as hundreds of inns run by local
farmers are now springing up everywhere.
</P>
<P>
These small hotels have attracted a great many foreigners
with their pure Tibetan style and good service.
</P>
<P>
"Tibet has charming scenery and this Tibetan inn is very
comfortable," says an Australian visitor to Tibet, who is staying
at the Khahu Inn run by Tsethri, a local farmer in Tingri County.
</P>
<P>
Tsethri and his family used to lead a poor farming life. But
his fate changed after he got a bank loan of 25,000 yuan and
opened a three-room inn nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
Tsethri opened his small hotel on the roadside of the
Sino-Nepalese Highway, the so-called "golden tourism route"
linking the two countries.
</P>
<P>
With the number of tourists going to Tibet increasing every
year, Tsethri's business is becoming booming, and his inn
now has 15 rooms and 44 beds.
</P>
<P>
"More than 1,000 foreigners stay at our hotel every year,"
Tsethri's mother Nyma says with a broad smile, adding that they
have paid off their loan. Their yearly earnings from the hotel
is now 30,000 to 40,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
For Pemba from Quxia Village in Pasum Township the hotel
business has brought his family greater income to go along with
their earnings from farming and cattle and sheep raising.
</P>
<P>
Every year, Pemba earns more than 20,000 yuan from the hotel
which stands along the very road leading to Mount Qomolangma
(Everest). "In the past, we led a poor life at the foot of
Qomolangma," he recalls.
</P>
<P>
Pemba's family now lives in a two-story house equipped with a
solar heater, a refrigerator and color TV.
</P>
<P>
More Tibetan farmers are taking advantage of the flourishing
tourism industry, and currently, there are 300 to 400 country inns
in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, Tibet received 82,000 foreign
tourists last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
