<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Nigerian Leader to Pursue Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton urged visiting Nigerian leader Abdulsalami Abubakar on
Wednesday to continue his country's transition to democracy, a
U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Abubakar met for about 30 minutes at the White
House, the official said.
</P>
<P>
"The president expressed his support for General Abubakar's
efforts. He stressed how important Nigeria's transition to
democracy is for all of Africa," the U.S. official said. "This is
a moment that must be seized."
</P>
<P>
After Nigeria's late dictator Sani Abacha died in June,
Abubakar and Nigeria's ruling generals created a commission to
oversee preparations for a return to civilian rule next May.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Washington had no current plans to lift its military and other
sanctions on Nigeria, but he suggested the issue would be under
consideration as Nigeria moved toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
"It is something we need to review as appropriate in the
context of this transition," the official said. "We are not at a
decision point currently."
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the Clinton-Abubakar meeting, the
White House hinted it might offer closer ties to Nigeria if the
African country carried out democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
"The president expressed his strong appreciation for the
efforts of General Abubakar to progress toward a new era of
democracy, respect for human rights, and stability, which will
lead to further expansion of our bilateral relations," it said.
</P>
<P>
After Abacha seized power in 1993, Washington imposed a series
of sanctions on Lagos, which included limiting military sales,
banning direct air links, and restricting visas for senior
Nigerian officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
