<HEADLINE> International Conference On Vehicle Theft Concludes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The international conference on
"Insurance Fraud, Theft and the Illegal Traffic in Motor Vehicles"
concluded here on Wednesday with agreements on broader cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The conference, convened on Monday, reached agreements on
building closer cooperation between law enforcement authorities,
insurance companies and other relevant bodies and organizations at
the national and international levels in various countries.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from 20 European countries, the United States and
Canada decided to organize similar international conference on a
regular basis.
</P>
<P>
Concluding recommendations show the conference approved the
initiative of the Bulgarian Interior Ministry, which also received
the support of Interpol, for the second international forum to be
held again in Sofia in the second half of September 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to recommendations, customs authorities and auto
manufacturers should make more thorough presentations at the next
conference.
</P>
<P>
Interpol's database will be expanded by attracting other
participating countries and their investigative agencies.
</P>
<P>
The conference recommends conventions, agreements and other
accords to create uniform legislation throughout different
countries in the fight against auto insurance fraud, theft and
illegal trafficking in motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The conference was useful because of the opportunity it
provided to establish contacts with colleagues in European
countries. These personal contacts will facilitate future
operations, a Bulgarian participant and representative of the
Interior Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Interpol has more than 1.1 million stolen cars registered as of
September 1, according to Interpol Secretary-General Raymond
Kendall, who was also a participant in the conference.
</P>
<P>
Most of the stolen cars originated in Germany, followed by
several East European countries. Bulgaria is the sixth on the
list. The country has become one of the channels for transiting
and selling cars stolen from Western Europe to the markets of the
former Soviet Union and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
On September 21, Bulgarian authorities arrested three car-theft
rings and 38 criminal groups. About 687 stolen cars were found and
20 luxury cars from Canada were also confiscated, said
Kendall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
