<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Government Wins 30th Confidence Vote in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government won its
30th confidence vote in parliament Wednesday, forcing through tax
collection reforms it sees essential to realize the revenue in the
1999 budget.
</P>
<P>
The reforms involve a tightening up of the tax collection
system, which, according to the government's draft budget, will
garner four trillion lire (2.35 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Vincenzo Visco said the confidence vote was
necessary to get the reforms in place in time to bear fruit in the
1999 accounts.
</P>
<P>
"There was not enough time for the law to return to the lower
house", he said in a speech before the vote in the Senate.
Normally the measures would have had a second reading in both
houses before being passed into law.
</P>
<P>
Visco said the planned changes in tax collection procedures
were "an important part of the wider reform of the fiscal system,"
which he had been pursuing since the center-left government of
Romano Prodi came to power.
</P>
<P>
"This measure, which is tied to the budget, accelerates tax
collection rather than introducing new taxes", he added.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in several years the government's budget
bill for 1999, which aims to squeeze an extra 13.5 trillion lire
(7.94 billion dollars) out of state accounts, contains no new
taxes.
</P>
<P>
The government won the confidence vote with 160 in favour and
99 against. There was a clean divide between parties supporting
the government on the one side and the opposition on the other.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
