<HEADLINE> Colombian State Employees Start National Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Some 600,000
Colombian state employees Wednesday started a nationwide two-day
strike to protest against the government's economic policies and
demand a higher pay rise in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The walkout was the first one held by national state employees
after President Andres Pastrana took office in early August.
</P>
<P>
Public Finance Minister Juan Camilo Restrepo said the strike
was passing peacefully throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The government has announced a wage rise of 14 percent for
state employees next year, but civil servants are demanding higher
increase.
</P>
<P>
Labor Minister Hernando Yepes said that those who took part in
the strike would not be paid. He also urged the unions to sit
down for talks with the government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the "Central Strike Command" of three unions, which
is organizing the strike, warned that they would call another
national strike in October if no agreement was reached. 
</P>
