<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Apples, Money-earner For Northern Chinese Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Apples have become the leading
money-earner for Shaanxi Province, bringing 8 billion yuan (963.8
million US dollars) a year to the loess plateau of northern China.
</P>
<P>
The province has 533,000 hectares of apple trees, making it
China's second largest apple-grower, after Shandong
Province. Large-scale apple tree planting started in the mid-1980s
and has fundamentally changed the life of farmers who for
generations relied on small-scale grain production on barren land.
</P>
<P>
Wang Tianlai, a 62-year-old farmer, got enough money from his
0.4 hectare orchard to build a three-story house and put thousands
of yuan in banks, and he is just one of the farmers in the arid,
hilly area north of the Wei River who were able to get away from
poverty when the area became a major apple producer.
</P>
<P>
The over 27 million farmers in Shaanxi farmers get an average
of 157 yuan from apples, and the per capita profits of farmers
near the Wei is as high as 1,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
One apple storage and transport company has 10 million yuan in
assets and caters to the international market, providing 50
million kilograms of apples a year, and one apple juice company
has an annual output of 10,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, fresh apples were worth 6.1 billion yuan, apple storage
1.2 billion yuan, and packing and processing 600 million yuan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
