<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 24 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The standard of living of the Chinese has improved along
with the economic development of the past 20 years, according to
the State Statistics Bureau, and people are now earning more in
more different ways.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in 1997 per capita disposable income of
urban Chinese was 5,160 yuan, 3.1 times that of 1978, and per
capita net income of rural residents was 2,090 yuan, 4.4 times
1978's figure.
</P>
<P>
Spending habits have also changed, with Chinese now spending
more on entertainment and services, instead of just food and
clothing.
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, China's leading lawmaker, met yesterday with
Lithuanian Procurator-General Kazys Pednycia.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the National People's Congress Standing
Committee, told Pednycia that the education and rectification
campaigns China's Supreme People's Procuratorate (SPP) and Supreme
People's Court (SPC) have carried out over the past few months
have achieved what he termed "phased results".
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Peng, chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC)
Standing Committee, said yesterday that China is fully prepared to
promote Sino-Romanian friendship and cooperation on the basis of
equality, mutual benefit and respect.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks during a meeting with the Romanian Senate
Chairman Petre Roman.
</P>
<P>
-- Zeng Peiyan, minister of the State Development Planning
Commission, yesterday voiced strong confidence in China's ability
to achieve its economic goals for 1998 and said its currency will
not be devalued.
</P>
<P>
-- Koo Chen-fu, chairman of the Taiwan Straits Exchange
Foundation(SEF), will meet with Wang Daohan, president of the
Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS), in
Shanghai in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to yesterday's agreement reached by ARATS and SEF
officials, Koo will lead a delegation to Shanghai and Beijing
between October 14-19.
