<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Company Launches Huge Y2K Database </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A leading American
company in information services industry has launched a Web site
providing free access to information on year 2000 (Y2K) computer
problems, according to a press release of the company reaching
here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The site Vendor 2000, launched by Electronic Data Systems
(EDS), now includes information on more than 129,000 products from
3,400 vendors and is still growing.
</P>
<P>
EDS said that it built and has maintained the Web-based data
over the past four years to bolster internal corporate and
customer research of the Year 2000 issues.
</P>
<P>
Vendor 2000, whose data is updated daily, is the world's
largest such database covering information technology assets such
as hardware, software, network, operating systems and physical
plant equipment, the company said.
</P>
<P>
Visitors to the site are able to search for compliance by
product and by vendor, by clicking on "product search," which
opens the database automatically and alphabetically. A link is
provided directly to vendor home pages for further inquiry.
</P>
<P>
Most older software was written with two-digit date fields that
are likely to read the "00" in 2000 as "1900" and therefore, fail
to make correct calculations. Companies and government agencies
worldwide have been scrambling to fix such software or to scrap it
altogether and implement new systems.
</P>
<P>
With less than 500 days left to the year 2000, EDS said, people
need to be working together to address this issue. "This tool
(Vendor 2000) will allow many to jump start compliance efforts
whether it be governments, businesses or consumers," it said.
</P>
<P>
At an EDS press conference Monday, John Koshinen, chairman of
U.S. President's Council on Year 2000, said: "Information and the
exchange of information is a critical part of being able to
remediate Y2K problems worldwide." The Council will have a link
from its Web site to the Vendor 2000 site within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
EDS is not the only company to launch such a Web site. A newly
launched "Y2K today" service is designed to provide current news,
opinions and analysis as well as status reports and strategies for
year 2000 progress and compliance.
</P>
<P>
Both this and EDS sites are intended to provide a forum for
discussions. Vendor 2000 will allow users of various products to
post comments regarding testing procedures and implementation of
products.
</P>
<P>
EDS, which employs 110,000 people, serves clients in 45
countries and reported revenues of 15.2 billion U.S. dollars in
1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0302 </DOCNO>
