<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Winter Olympics Budget to be Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Organizing Committee
of the 2002 Salt Lake Winter Olympics will reveal its 1
billion-plus US dollars budget on Thursday, according to a report
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The committee's board of trustees is expected to vote on the
proposed spending package during a meeting schedulted for October
8. SLOC's executive board was given a preview of the 45-volume
budget plan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Putting on the Olympics is a very large project," SLOC
chairman Robert Garff, a local car dealer and former state
legislator, said after Wednesday's meeting. "I think the
executive board was impressed with the depth of the work by the
staff."
</P>
<P>
Following earlier budget sessions with SLOC's budget
committee, Alan Layton, committee chairman and head of a
construction company, said: "We're not putting on a country fair
and we're not planning the Normandy invasion. But it's a lot
closer to the Normandy invasion."
</P>
<P>
The Salt Lake spending plan covers 42 functions, such as
medical services or security, 200-plus projects, like the torch
relay, 400 subprojects and 3,000 activities, such as three
planting.
</P>
<P>
According to the committee, taxpayers have already been docked
59 million US dollars to build Olympic venues.
</P>
<P>
Constructions are going on at Utah Winter Sports Park, the
speedskating oval in Kearns and the cross-country and biathlon
courses at Wasatch Mountain State Park.
</P>
<P>
The proposed budget includes repayment of the 59 million
dollars and sets aside a 40 million dollars endowment to pay for
site operations after the 2002 Games.
</P>
<P>
The first budget organizers drafted was in 1989 for 400
million dollars and the latest revision in 1996 ranged from 920
million to 1.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The earlier budget predicted SLOC would gain 920 million
dollars from television rights, corporate sponsorships and ticket
sales. The estimated value of donated goods and services ranged
from 266 million to 336 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the 1998 Winter Games in Japan said they broke
even on their 956 million dollars budget. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
