<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flo-Jo Family Gets Angry with Drug Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The sudden death of
Florence Griffith Joyner caused speculation that the former
Olympic champion may have used performance enhancing drugs, but
her family denied angryly that she took any drugs.
</P>
<P>
"How would you feel if someone was spreading false rumors
about you and your daughter had to read about this?" Bob Kersee,
Griffith Joyner's former coach, said Tuesday. Griffith Joyner was
the mother of a 7-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
Griffith Joyner, who blazed down the track to set a fabulous
world record of 10.49 seconds in the 100 meters, and created
another world record in the 200 meters at Seoul Olympics in 1988,
died early Monday in her sleep at age of 38.
</P>
<P>
Autopsy tests were continuing. Greg Foster, a three-time world
champion in the 110-meter hurdles, said he was told by her family
that Griffith Joyner died of a heart problem.
</P>
<P>
Although she never failed a drug test, accusations that she
used performance-enhancing drugs had been leveled against her in
the past. Her surprising death renewed such talks.
</P>
<P>
In belgium the chairman of the International Olympic
Committee's medical commission said today that the sprinter was
subjected to rigorous examination at the 1988 games and passed
every test.
</P>
<P>
"So there should not be the slightest suspicion," Prince
Alexandre de Merode said. "Let her rest in peace. The issue is
closed."
</P>
<P>
Her sister-in-law, Olympic gold medalist Jackie Joyner-Kersee,
urged everyone to wait for the autopsy findings and said it was
inappropriate to speculate.
</P>
<P>
Bob Kersee said Griffith Joyner had no history of heart
troubles. "She only suffered from exercise-induced asthma and
migraine headaches."
</P>
<P>
In 1989, U.S. sprinter Darrell Robinson said in the German
magazine Stern that he bought banned growth hormones for Griffith
Joyner. Robinson was paid 25,000 US dollars for his interview
with the magazine.
</P>
<P>
Griffith Joyner had denied Robinson's charge, calling him a
"compulsive, crazy, lying lunatic."
</P>
<P>
Arne Ljungqvist, vice president of the International Amateur
Athletics Federation and the organization's top anti-drug
official, said it would be unfair to speculate about Griffith
Joyner and performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
"It's very unfortunate for sport if one is accused of doping
just for being an extremely good athlete," he said.
</P>
<P>
Funeral arrangements have not been announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
