<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sees Kosovo Issue Internal Matter of FRY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- "China has always been
of the view that the question of Kosovo is an internal matter of
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY)" and "the question of
Kosovo should and can only be solved by the Yugoslavian people
themselves," a senior Chinese diplomat said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations, made the remarks at the formal consultations by the
Security Council on a draft resolution on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"An ultimate solution can only be chosen by the Yugoslavian
people themselves," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate the position of the Government of FRY for a
settlement of the Kosovo issue through unconditional dialogue," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The situation in the Kosovo region is now stabilizing, and
there is no large-scale armed conflict, still less than any
escalation of the conflict, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The Government of FRY has also taken a series of positive
measures to encourage the refugees to return home and provide
facilities for humanitarian relief of work," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that "at the same time, we are gravely
concerned about the act," as pointed out in the September 4 report
by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, "of blocking the return of
refugees for political purposes and prolonging the humanitarian
crisis so as to keep the attention of the international community
in this region."
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the international community should look at
the current situation in Kosovo as it really is and evaluating
the positive efforts by the Government of FRY in an objective
and just manner," he said, "We do not see the situation in
Kosovo as a threat to international peace and security."
</P>
<P>
"I would like to reiterate here that many countries in the FRY
region are multi-ethnic," he said, "If the Security Council is to
get involved in a dispute without the request from countries
concerned, or go even further as to unfairly apply pressure on or
threaten actions against the government of the country concerned,
it will create a bad precedent and have wider negative
implications."
</P>
<P>
On the draft resolution, Qin said that it "has not taken into
full consideration in Kosovo and the legitimate rights of FRY
within its sphere of sovereignty, and has invoked Chapter 7 of
the U.N. Charter all too indiscreetly to threaten FRY."
</P>
<P>
"This will not help bring about a fundamental settlement of
the Kosovo issue," he said, "It may, on the contrary, reinforce
the separatist and terrorist forces in the region and intensify
the tension there."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, "the Chinese delegation can not support the draft
resolution before us and will abstain," Qin added.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, a province of Serbia within the FRY, where ethnic
Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the province's 2 million
people, seek independence from Yugoslavia. The conflict broke
out in February this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
