<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Pakistan to talk on Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 23 (Xinhua) -- India and Pakistan on
Wednesday agreed to resume their peace dialogue on Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
This was announced in a statement issued after a meeting
between Indian Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee and his
Pakistani counterpart Nawaz Sharif at a New York hotel.
</P>
<P>
The two heads of government agreed during their luncheon talks
that their foreign secretaries would open talks on a number of
issues, including Jammu and Kashmir in Islamabad October 15-18,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"They reaffirmed their common belief that an environment of
durable peace and security was in the supreme interest of both
India and Pakistan, and of the region as a whole," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"They agreed that the peaceful settlement of all outstanding
issues, including Jammu and Kashmir was essential for this
purpose," it added.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee and Sharif are also said to be willing to talk about
the disarmament issue after their countries' nuclear tests in May.
The tests drew international condemnations and a call for their
signing of the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT).
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee told reporters on his way to New York to attend the
53rd session of the U.N. General Assembly that India would sign
the CTBT as a nuclear weapon power only its conditions are
fulfilled, but he did not specify the conditions.
</P>
<P>
India has firmly rejected deadlines the United States has been
trying to set for New Delhi to sign CTBT by attempting to link it
to President Bill Clinton's visit to India, Press Trust of India
said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee is scheduled to speak at the U.N. session on Thursday,
a day after Sharif did.
</P>
<P>
Sharif told the U.N. General Assembly on Wednesday that
Pakistan is prepared to adhere to the CTBT before the Conference
of States Parties to the CTBT is held in September 1999.
</P>
<P>
"However, Pakistan's adherence to the Treaty will take place
only in conditions free from coercion or pressure," he said.
</P>
<P>
He told Clinton on Monday that Pakistan had no objection in
principle to signing the CTBT but wanted the United States to
waive economic sanctions first. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980924.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Ceasefire in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 23 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council
on Wednesday adopted a resolution on Kosovo issue, threatening
with "further action and additional measures to maintain or
restore peace and stability in the region." China abstained from
voting.
</P>
<P>
The resolution is taken for the first time under Chapter 7 of
the U.N. Charter, which makes compliance mandatory. The resolution
said that "The deterioration of the situation in Kosovo, the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY), constitutes a threat to
peace and security in the region."
</P>
<P>
Shortly before his abstention from voting, Qin Huansun, Chinese
permanent representative to the United Nations, said that the
draft resolution, which failed to take into full consideration the
situation in Kosovo and the legitimate rights of FRY within its
sphere of sovereignty, will not help bring about a fundamental
settlement of the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
"It may, on the contrary, reinforce the separatist and
terrorist forces in the region and intensify the tension there,"
said the Chinese envoy, who said the Kosovo issue is an internal
matter of the FRY, and the international community should
refrain from involvement into the question.
</P>
<P>
"If the Security Council is to get involved in a dispute
without the request from countries concerned, or go even further
as to unfairly apply pressure on or threaten actions against the
government of the country concerned, it will create a bad
precedent and have wider negative implications," he said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution called upon all parties, groups and individuals
to "immediately cease hostilities and maintain a ceasefire in
Kosovo, which would enhance the prospects for a meaningful
dialogue between the authorities of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia and the Kosovo Albanian leadership and reduce the risks
of a humanitarian catastrophe."
</P>
<P>
The resolution urged the FRY authorities and the Kosovo
Albanian leadership "to enter immediately into a meaningful
dialogue without preconditions and with international involvement,
and to a clear timetable, leading to an end of the crisis and to a
negotiated political solution to the issue of Kosovo, and welcomes
the current efforts aimed at facilitating such a dialogue."
</P>
<P>
The resolution also called for an end to all action by the
security forces affecting the civilian population and order the
withdrawal of security units used for civilian repression.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, reiterating the commitment of all Security
Council to the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the FRY,
endorsed the steps taken to establish effective international
monitoring of the situation in Kosovo, a province in Serbia of the
FRY.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council decided, if necessary, to "consider
further action and additional measures to maintain or restore
peace and stability in the region," according to the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The resolution is seen giving green lights to the NATO, which
has hammered out a contingency plans in response to what it said
the deteriorating situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, with an area of more than 100,000 square kilometers and
a population of 2 million, is a province in Serbia of the FRY.
Ethnic Albanians, making up 90 percent of the province's
population, have demanded independence of Kosovo. The conflict
broke out in February this year in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
