<HEADLINE> Everton Signs Tranmere Goalkeeper at Record Price </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Everton set a British record
fee for a goalkeeper after signing Tranmere's 19-year-old Steve
Simonsen at a price of 3.3 million pounds (about 5.5 million U.S.
dollars) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The England under-21 keeper's switch across the Mersey River
from first division Tranmere to Goodison Park -- with Graham
Allen going the other way as part of the deal -- breaks the
previous record of 2.25 million pounds (3.78 million U.S.
dollars) when Nigel Martyn moved from Crystal Palace to Leeds in
July 1996.
</P>
<P>
"It is a dream move for me. It is a big club and the players
here are brilliant," said Simonsen, who was born in South
Shields, north-east England and who won't be 20 until next April
3.
</P>
<P>
"There are plenty of top class internationals and hopefully we
will be a team that can get up amongst the top dogs in the
Premier league", Simonsen said on Everton's Clubcall.
</P>
<P>
Simonsen's arrival is sure to put pressure on current Everton
No. 1 Thomas Myhre. But Simonsen believes it will be difficult
to dislodge the Norwegian international.
</P>
<P>
He said: "Thomas has been brilliant since he came to the club
and he will be great competition. I think he is looking forward
to it as much as I am."
</P>
<P>
The move represents a meteroric rise for the player who was
Tranmere's third choice keeper at the start of last season.
</P>
<P>
After breaking into the team last November, Simonsen kept his
place until the end of the season and kept seven clean sheets in
cup and league matches between December and January. He has been
capped Under-18 and Under-21 level by England. 
</P>
</TEXT>
