<HEADLINE> Crystal Palace Sets Sights on Sheringham </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- English First Division club
Crystal Palace chairman Mark Goldberg confirmed Wednesday his
interest in buying England striker Teddy Sheringham.
</P>
<P>
Goldberg is determined to reverse Palace's dismal performance
in the First Division, with last Saturday's 4-0 defeat at
Barnsley leaving them with just seven points from seven league
games.
</P>
<P>
Despite more than half a dozen new signings over the summer,
Goldberg is prepared to fund even more purchases in the wake of
the recent sales of Hermann Hreidarsson and Neil Shipperley.
</P>
<P>
He is also understood to be open to offers for utility player
Paul Warhurst and Italian striker Michele Padovano.
</P>
<P>
Sheringham, who faces a tough time behind Dwight Yorke, Andy
Cole, Ole Gunnar Solksjaer and Paul Scholes at United is thought
to be top of Goldberg's list.
</P>
<P>
Palace hopes that United will be willing to sell him, with
reports indicating that a fee of 3.5 million pounds could be
involved.
</P>
<P>
Goldberg has also been linked with possible moves for
Portsmouth striker John Aloisi and Queens Park Rangers forward
Kevin Gallen, though he also has his sights set firmly on Europe.
</P>
<P>
The Palace chairman and coach Terry Venebles both flew to
watch one target in action on Wednesday, missing the second leg
of the Eagles' Worthington Cup clash with Bury.
</P>
<P>
"We're not prepared to sit back after the recent defeats,"
Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
"Action is what is required and action is what is being
intended right now.
</P>
<P>
"Terry and I are out looking this week at players with a view
to rebuilding our squad.
</P>
<P>
"Teddy Sheringham is one of those targets," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
