<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Panel Approves Alternate AIDS Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Senate committee on
Wednesday approved a legislation that would enable hemophiliacs
who contracted AIDS before the government acted to safeguard the
blood supply to get 100,000 U.S. dollars as compensation.
</P>
<P>
The Labor and Human Resources Committee also approved an
alternate bill that would add compensation for other people who
contracted the virus through blood transfusions.
</P>
<P>
The money would go to the AIDS victims themselves, or their
survivors if they have died.
</P>
<P>
The government began safeguarding the blood supply in the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
In May, the House approved legislation to aid 7,200
hemophiliacs. But the Senate panel included some 10,000
transfusion victims.
</P>
<P>
Hemophiliacs fear that expanding the bill will make it too
controversial to pass in the remaining weeks before Congress
adjourns early October. They suggest Congress should come back and
compensate transfusion victims next year.
</P>
<P>
Considering that Congress will not take up the same issue again
next year, the Senate committee approved the alternate measure,
which would authorize funding for both groups. However
hemophiliacs would apply for the money six months before
transfusion victims could submit applications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
