<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Royal Heir Visits U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia's Crown
Prince Abdullah arrived here on Wednesday for a week-long visit
that will focus on tensions in the Gulf region and the impact of
low oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The prince was welcomed at Andrews Air Force Base near
Washington by Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah will meet with President Bill Clinton at the White
House on Thursday and other administration officials in the coming
days on what a State Department official called a "get-to-know-you
visit."
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials were expected to press him for the latest status
of a Saudi investigation into the June 1996 truck bomb at the
Khobar Towers compound housing U.S. forces near Dhahran.
</P>
<P>
The impact of low world oil prices on future Saudi purchasing
is likely to be raised at the meetings. This could have a serious
impact for the United States, which is the largest exporter of
goods to the Arab state.
</P>
<P>
Prince Abdullah began a world tour last week with visits to
Britain and France. It is the first major trip to the West since
1987 for the prince, who has travelled little outside his region.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's biggest oil producer and an important
U.S. ally, played a key role in the coalition that drove invading
Iraqi forces out of Kuwait in 1991.
</P>
<P>
But, like other regional states, it has been reluctant to take
an aggressive stand against Iraqi President Saddam Hussein in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah is scheduled to meet with Gore, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, Deputy
Secretary of Defense John Hamre, other administration officials as
well as congressional leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
