<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Backs SADC Intervention in Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe said Wednesday
that it fully supported the joint military intervention by South
Africa and Botswana to restore peace and stability in Lesotho,
according to a report from Harare, capital of Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The office of Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said in a
statement that Zimbabwe, as one of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) countries and a member of the SADC
task force on Lesotho, could not accept a situation where a
constitutionally-elected government was made to operate at the
instructions of the army.
</P>
<P>
Instead, the statement stressed, the army should give
allegiance to the government.
</P>
<P>
At request of the Lesotho cabinet, troops from South Africa
and Botswana have crossed into Lesotho since Tuesday to restore
law and order to the internal conflict which had threatened peace
and stability there.
</P>
<P>
"Any military attack to undermine a sovereign government is
viewed by all of us in SADC and the OAU (Organization of African
Unity) as rebellious and therefore as matter of great concern
requiring immediate redress wherever it occurs," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Developments in Lesotho during the past week had clearly shown
that law and order had broken down irretrievably and the
situation needed urgent intervention.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to pledge full support to the government of Prime
Minister Pakalitha Mosisili and therefore to our joint SADC force
which is currently helping to secure the tenure of that
legitimate government," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho has been in tense situation following the opposition's
refusal to accept the May 23 general elections which they claimed
were rigged by Mosisili's government.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties insisted that the results of the
general elections allegedly rigged by the ruling party must be
annulled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
