<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seven Arrested in London in Connection with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- British police said on
Wednesday they have arrested seven men thought to be linked to
Islamic groups in an anti-terrorist operation.
</P>
<P>
The operation was a joint one between specialist police
officers from Special Branch and MI5, the domestic military
intelligence arm.
</P>
<P>
The seven men, some of whom Egyptians and one Saudi, were
picked up at separate addresses in north-west and west London
early Wednesday morning, a police spokeswoman said. An eighth
address, a business premises, was also searched.
</P>
<P>
The men, arrested under the Prevention of Terrorism Act, were
believed to have links with Osama bin Laden, the Saudi Arabian
terrorist currently in hiding, the spokeswoman added.
</P>
<P>
Last month Britain rushed through tough anti-terrorist
legislation in the wake of a huge car bomb in the Northern Irish
town of Omagh, in which 29 people were killed.
</P>
<P>
Under the new laws, conspiring to commit terrorist crimes
abroad while in Britain will become an offence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
