<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela Cites Problems in Proposed Lockerbie Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said on Wednesday that there are still three snags
in the resolution of the Lockerbie bombing trial.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the end of a visit to Washington,
Mandela said progress was being made toward an arrangement for the
suspects to be tried in the Netherlands and that Libyan leader
Muammar Gaddafi was cooperating.
</P>
<P>
An American-British proposal unveiled on August 24 said that
the suspects in the bombing of a Pan Am airliner over Lockerbie,
Scotland, which killed 270 people, would be tried in the
Netherlands by Scottish judges.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said Gaddafi was objecting to a request that he
guarantee to make available any Libyans who were called as
witnesses in the trial.
</P>
<P>
"I know of no system of jurisprudence anywhere in the world
where the accused is required to produce witnesses for the
prosecution," Mandela said, saying this is the first problem.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, he supported Gaddafi's objection to British
suggestions that if the men were found guilty and sentenced to
prison terms they would serve those sentences in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he could see no logic in this and added that as
Britain and Libya have no diplomatic relations, the Libyans would
have no recourse if they were ill-treated in prison.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, Mandela also expressed his objection to the plan that
was the trial will be held in a former American military base. It
was essential to establish that no U.S. troops would be present,
he said, adding he had raised this with President Bill Clinton
during his stay in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"If there is even one American soldier it is going to create
problems. I hope that matter will be resolved, because President
Gaddafi is cooperating," he said.
</P>
<P>
The South African leader said he had been working with Saudi
King Fahd, though their diplomats in Washington, to try to resolve
the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
