<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Jump Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 23 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks shot higher
today as Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan once again
stressed concerns about an impending crisis in the global economy,
though giving no clear signal of an immediate cut in interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average surged to 8,154.41 by the
close, up 257.21 points, or 3.3 percent. It is the highest finish
in a month, with more than half of the gain coming during the
final hour of trading.
</P>
<P>
The gain, the fifth-biggest in points for a single session,
left the Dow more than 200 points above this year's starting point
of 7,908.25, but still about 1,200 below the July 17 record of
9,337.97.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 36.46 to 1,066.09, and the
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 62.47 to 1,760.27.
</P>
<P>
Advancers beat decliners by a 3-to-1 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 902.88 million shares as
against, up sharply from 687.19 million at the same point on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 16.35 to 526.95, and the American
Stock Exchange composite index rose 12.63 to 646.08.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 7.76 to
376.00.  
</P>
</TEXT>
