<HEADLINE> IDB Approves Large Loan of $1.35 Bln for Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 23 (Xinhua) -- A 3.3 billion U.S. dollar
fund is established by three banks to support microenterprise and
small businesses in Brazil, the IDB President Enrique V. Iglesias
said here Wednesday
</P>
<P>
The Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), the Banco Nacional
de Desenvolvimento Economico e Social of Brazil (BNDE) and the
Export-Import Bank of Japan have agreed to each provide 1.1
billion U.S. dollars to form a 3.3 billion dollar fund for Brazil.
</P>
<P>
"This is the biggest loan in the history of the Bank," said
Iglesias. "Support for these small enterprises is critical for the
improvement of their productivity and for creating a large number
of employment opportunities."
</P>
<P>
The fund will also finance private sector services in education
and health.
</P>
<P>
In another operation, the IDB today also approved a 250 million
dollar loan to Brazil to help improve low-income neighborhoods,
bringing today's total financing to 1.35 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the IDB has also okayed 200 million in previous
loans to Brazil in such sectors as informatics, legislative
modernization, environmental protection, municipal development
and private sector electric power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
